text:
i had a dream last night...
a nightmare if you will.
a past i tried so hard to forget.
memories i attempted to erase.
awoken in a sweat feeling like i’m back in that moment.
heart pounding through my chest.
i’m there
watching as the events unfold.
but why?
what am i supposed to gain from watching myself hurt? 
what am i supposed to learn from the scariest moment in my life?
in that moment i wanted to die.
i thought i would never get through the darkness that had consumed me.
that’s when it hit me like a ton of bricks.
and then i woke up.
it all makes sense now.
it gets better.
if i can do it so can you.
choose to be the light.
choose to see the bright side.
choose to be the smile someone needed.
choose to spread love.
we all have our own stories... what made us who we are.
don’t forget who you are and what you are capable of.
everyday is a choice.
 so what are you going to choose?

•

text:
1/19/19: the #womenswave. women's march: petaluma
saturday, january 19, 2019
11:00 am  3:00 pm

two year’s since the first women’s march and two years into the trump presidency, it’s time to march again. this time the focus is on the women’s wave, a paradigm shift that brings in #metoo and the record numbers of women entering congress. let’s keep the momentum going.

we’ll be heading to the sister march in petaluma and we’re hoping to have a group from the indie alley so that we can make all our voices heard. we’ll create banners the morning of the march, then carpool together to petaluma. 
if you want to join us, please rsvp by wednesday january 16th by emailing hello@theindiealley.com, so that we can figure out the logistics. 
together, we can do this.
#womenswave #womensmarch #sistermarch

text:
as we begin planning for 2019, it's important to reflect on what made 2018 such a special year. 2018 is being referred to as "year of the woman" due to the strides women have made throughout the country. at ywca, we had a lot of work to make this happen here at home in union county. 
as the #metoo movement was gaining traction nationally and internationally, we had our 5th annual dv symposium at kean university to lead an open discussion about consent. a month before the historic midterm elections, we celebrated women's leadership by honoring female elected officials throughout union county and the state of new jersey at our 40th anniversary gala. but women's leadership is not exclusive to government. at our 39th annual tribute to women in industry, we honored working women in various fields. 
thank you to all who helped make 2018 such a memorable year. while there were plenty of reasons to celebrate, there is still much work to do in 2019 and years to come to further our mission of eliminating racism and empowering women.

text: have you seen #survivingrkelly? if you are involved in or been following the #metoo movement it is your duty to watch this, share it, and/or speak out about it. this movement was originally created by #taranaburke in response to the violence againast young black girls which this film explicitly outlines. i couldn’t sleep last night after watching this, thinking of all of the young black girls lives who were ruined and the ways in which we have all been complicit. years ago i began to boycott anything to do with r. kelly, and today i pledge to follow the lead of black women organizers and activists working on this issue and to speak out. please do not look away because you feel this isn’t your issue, or you can’t relate, or you don’t want to be triggered or your a white person and feel uncomfortable. this is an issue we must unite and organize around to show our black and brown sisters that their lives matter. you can watch the series on lifetime or buy it as i did on amazon. take the time to watch it and discuss it, these lives matter and need our support! and if watching this would be too triggering there are other ways to take action. share it, call mca, or volunteer at a hotline. p.s. if this is the first time you are hearing about this series, please take that as an indication that part of the work that needs to be done is to diversify your circle of friends and community. everyone in the black community is talking about this. you should have seen this by now. and if you haven’t then that speaks for itself. everyone in the world heard about the kavanaugh hearings, but black women and girls lives doesn’t get the same attention. let’s do our part to make a change today. you can watch it here: https://www.mylifetime.com/shows/surviving-r-kelly
name: Celia Ward-Wallace

text: första gången jag blev våldtagen var jag 7 år gammal. det var en kille som var 8 år äldre än mig; min brors bästa vän. vi var ofta över hos hans familj eftersom  min mamma och pappa även var goda vänner med hans föräldrar. jag hade en liten crush på honom och jag kallade honom för min teddybjörn. detta var från låten teddybjörnen fredriksson (han heter fredrik) och det var en av mina favoritlåtar när jag var liten. nu klarar jag inte av att höra den. mina minnesluckor från våldtäkten är stora och ej kronologiska. det är för resten mina minnen av hela min uppväxt. jag har förträngt mycket. jag vet inte varför jag var ensam med fredrik på hans rum den dagen. jag vet inte hur länge han höll på med mig men jag minns att det gjorde ont när han stack in sina fingrar i mig. jag vet inte varför jag stelnade och inte så något. jag vet inte om jag grät. jag minns känslan av panik och att jag längtade efter att han skulle sluta. när mamma äntligen ropade på mig att det var dags att gå hem så blev jag så lättad och kravlade ur hans grepp. han sa bara att jag inte fick berätta något. när vi skulle gå och jag inte ville krama fredrik, som jag alltid annars gjorde, så skrattade bara alla vuxna och tvingade mig att göra det ändå. usch vad dåligt jag mådde då! när jag var 22 år gammal berättade jag för min familj för första gången. jag hade precis blivit mamma och nu insåg jag att jag hade varit med om något hemskt som barn. och ingen såg mina varningstecken. jag slutade med min sport. tröst-åt mitt i natten. fick bulimi och dålig självbild. jag var mobbad i skolan. började sedan skära mig själv. använde sex i tonåren som självskadebeteende. jag har nu ätit antidepressiva i 9 år. gått i kbt och talat med kuratorer. har även efter #metoo äntligen konfronterat min våldtäktsman som nekat till att han minns denna händelse. han har nu två små barn. det är endast därför jag kontaktade hans fru. jag önskar att inget barn någonsin ska behöva genomlida ett övergrepp! #treskablinoll #rape #övergrepp #utnyttjad #psykiskohälsa #minberättelse #inteensamaldrigglömd

text:
on day 10 of 25 days of january, i want to talk about body image.

because here's the truth:

complaining about your body won't make you healthier, skinnier, happier or help you love your body.

dissing your body actually makes it even harder to look after yourself properly.

weighing yourself doesn't make you healthier 
it makes you more obsessed with your weight and disordered around food.

loving your body or getting into healthy habits takes time

just like learning a new language or instrument. 
if you’ve been dieting your whole life, your journey will be up and down. 
and that's totally okay. 😊

my advice?

fake it until you make it!

tell yourself how much you love you the bits of your body and why.

thank them for being part of you

and slowly you'll start having more days of appreciation and fewer days of complaining.

dissing your body actually makes it even harder to look after yourself properly.

weighing yourself does not make you healthier 
it makes you more obsessed with your weight and disordered around food.

loving your body or getting into healthy habits takes time

just like learning a new language or instrument. 
if you’ve been dieting your whole life, your journey will be up and down. 
and that's totally okay. 😊

my advice?

fake it until you make it!

tell yourself how much you love you the bits of your body and why.

thank them for being pa of you

and slowly you'll sta having more days of appreciation and fewer days of complaining.

text_retweet:
the following is from @placentamagic - savanah kennedy. i encourage you all to share your stories, your trauma. get it out. purge it. burn it. and never return to the same system that abused you...
.
reposted from @placentamagic - “how do you feel your birth went?”
⠀
one of the many student midwives who’d practiced cervical checks on me sat stiffly next to me on the postpartum ward bed. i wanted to spit on her.
⠀
“it was great.” i said coldly, holding my small, 2 day old baby closer.
⠀⠀
her eyes darted downwards, presumably towards the papers in her hands, but i’d like to think that for a split second she felt some type of guilt or remorse.
⠀
“so what are you going to do to stop this from ever happening again?” she said catching my eyes once more.
⠀
that’s the moment i got it. i understood. the things done to me weren’t necessary or even accidental, they were retaliative. they were retaliative because of the money they lost when i refused unnecessary procedures and testing.
⠀
they were retaliative because i didn’t trust them after they misdiagnosed me 3 times, and i told them.
⠀
why did i tell them?
⠀
“oh excuse me — i mean, what birth control are we setting you up with?”
⠀
the next 30 minutes were spent listening to the girl drone on about her pseudo cycle pills and implants. after her spill i smiled and told her i was good.
⠀
then she told me that i would be pregnant again in the next year because ovulating women, “get too caught in the moment to remember protection”.
⠀
i don’t think i’ll ever forget how absolutely atrocious her presence in that room was.
⠀
#metoo
#mybirthtoo

second #weighinthursday for me 😬 i'm ⬇️ 3.4 pounds since last weeks weigh in. i've lost a total of 5 pounds since this journey began on 1-1-19 🏃‍♀️
i got an early start this morning because i have to run errands before the snow storm shows up tomorrow 🌨️ i completed...
stretching: 10 min
treadmill walking: 30:14 min
distance walked: 1.431 miles
after stretching: 10 minutes

i struggle with most everything that i try to do in life. i've always had to work twice as hard as others to get the same results. this can be super frustrating but when i reach my goals, i'm that much prouder of myself. go me! 🏋️‍♀️💪 i've worked really hard to make good lifestyle changes these last ten days. i struggle but i keep going. only i can change me 😉 
changing the physical is a breeze compared to the mental. one day at a time and i don't let the difficult days drag me down. i have a good cry now and then because these changes are challenging and my body aches from fibromyalgia. i struggle with thoughts of those that hurt me in the past and when they'll get their full karma. these are some of the mental changes i'm working on. life is extremely difficult but i keep going and improving myself. i promise myself to be the best version of me and to always stay fair and true. i have to stay kind, even when hypocrites laugh in my face because i told my #metoo story. people can be awful... stay strong 💪 and keep moving 🏃‍♀️
day 10 strong 🏋️‍♀️ now to figure out food for today 🥗

text:
in preparation for the installation at edward hopper house, i received permission to  photograph source material for the paintings in the space where the hoppers lived and worked on washington square north, in greenwich village. it’s a somewhat sentimental or romantic gesture, photographing a contemporary model in the hopper home, with the same light hopper would have painted from, positioning the figure in the same place jo would have posed--- the model role-playing jo, who was role-playing hopper’s “women”… but in the paintings that came from this process i was hoping to draw out the lost threads of jo’s particular history and connect it to contemporary concerns of agency, identity, access and power. in the final installation, jo’s influence is blaring from the walls, seeping into the space, while the expressionless figures, lost forever in thought, meditate on what could have been for jo and what could be for them. 
i’ll be giving a talk this weekend at the nyack public library with @etcolleary if you’re interested in hearing more:) special thanks to two talented  @moraviancollege art students! @jillianmcluhan the model who like jo, has a background in theater and was visibly shapeshifting and finding new characters in front of the camera. @erikasalus helped capture the images, bringing her technical prowess to each shot. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻❤️❤️❤️

text: obediance to norms of family and in saudi in society puts multiple restrictions on womens lives. there are of course families in saudi who do not practice honorculture but the majority does. and it is everything from covering fully, not going outside unless with a family member, not seeing friends, not working... not living... to marriage with a stranger just to get out of the house, starvation, abuse, imprisonment... being put in dar prisons for women for escaping the family or for disobeying. ending up spending your life in prison. all legal for families to practice in saudi according to male guardianship law- because family first and ”family knows best”- even if they restrict your life to a phone, food and water... or much less. thats not life. life is having a choice. #maleguardianshiphell #stopenslavingsaudiwomen #feminism #feminist #metoo #timesup #honorkilling #honor #shraf #honorabuse #womentogether #solidarity #humanrights #women #womensrights

text:
this is a tough one. probably one of the toughest books i’ve read in awhile. and let me first offer a disclaimer— this post/ book may be a trigger for survivors of sexual assault. it took me a really long time to get through this collection— and i’m still processing all of my feelings.
•
roxane gay collected a variety of essays written who have encountered “rape culture” in its various forms: sexual assault, rape, traumatic relationships, harassment etc. survivors share the most horrific moments in their lives and their words stick with you. in the introduction roxane gay touches on her personal story and how surviving her rape made her believe “it wasn’t that bad” because she didn’t have a gun to her head or a blade to her throat. rape culture is part of our every day lives. it’s not wanting to walk home alone at night in fear you’ll be targeted. it’s holding your keys in between your fingers as you walk to your car just in case. it’s not wanting to go to that family party because you don’t want to see that uncle, brother or cousin. it’s not believing women and saying “but he’s such a nice guy! he couldn’t have done that.” “she’s just being dramatic.” “they were drunk, who even remembers.”
•
this is not a “must-read”, this is not and should not be seen as required reading. the storytelling was out of this world. this book left me full of emotions. gut wrenching emotions, full of saddness, disgust, heartbreak and yet a sense of familiarity. in this collection there were women of color, white women, a man, old, young, immigrant. so many various identities were captured. so many voices.
•
“what i need is what most women need when they talk about the sexual violence they have endured. i need someone to listen. i need someone to believe me.”-stacey may flowes
•
#believewomen #metoo #notthatbad #bbmreads #roxanegay

text:
🌈
بخشی از سریال روایت ندیمه رو براتون میذارم که ببینید در همین جامعه‌ی خودمون با چه موجوداتی سر و کار داریم!

در انجیل حکم شده که زن نباید سوادش از مرد بیشتر باشه و در سکوت و خفا باید مطالعه کنه و هیچ زنی حق نداره در کار به مرد ارشد باشه... حالا فک کنید این قانون اعمال بشه.... نابخرد‌هایی هستن که در توجیه رفتار و اخلاق غیر انسانی همواره لفظ سخیف و احمقانه‌ی "قانون مملکت هست و باید رعایت بشه!" رو به کار میبرن!

قبلا گفتم بازم میگم، نگید قانونه! بگید "مملکت ارث بابام هست." باز اینجوری احساس نمیکنیم به شعورمون توهین کردید.

پ.ن: شخصیت اصلی این سریال لزبین هست و به زودی تو کانال قرار میدیم.

پ.ن: شخصیت اصلی این سریال لزبین هست و به زودی تو کانال قرار میدیم.

text:
i’m gonna caption this “quiet talks with a narc” so yesterday i had a new client and as soon as i got to his apartment for what should of been a 3 hour cleaning session turned into a 5 hour “life coaching “ session with a cleaning remix track 🤣. i actually shot this snap footage literally the night before unknowingly that it would be the visual segway to my experience . i finally “went in” on him...knowing that at anytime this man was gonna tell me to leave(prob not pay me either). i kept my voice calm ( it probably helped that even though this guy was a proud trump supporter, anti #metoo  and kept calling me “sweetie”, followed me around the whole time in 1100sqft .. but i was not ever angry with him once. i can accredit that to all the narcissists videos and lectures i have been watching all day for 7 days . so did i change this obviously lost narcissistic guy yesterday? prob not. but “everyone always agrees with me and tells me i’m right “  was what he was telling me. “ummm, warren, your not, doll, your not.” sidenote obviously since this was previously shot the audio is not him, it’s actually a lecture i was totally enamored with dr. gabor maté! he explains with clinical proof how our disease from physical to neurological to emotional all stems from early childhood and generational history. link>> https://youtu.be/lsbrrvqaas8
. #familycurse #enjoythesilence #sorrynotsorry #talkswithnarcs #lecture

text: today in social justice. a class that was created to create an intentional, safe place for students to talk about “where we started”, what’s going on in our world today, and what we can do to spark change. this is one of the first times at marshall that i’ve felt like my experience is valued, that i’m not the only one, that i’m actually apart of the conversation. in the following posts i’ll reflect on each day/subject we covered including: multigenerational trauma and cultural resiliency, lgbtqia+, black loves matter, #metoo, and allyship

text:
：卡卡站出來為自己與被性侵者發聲‼️
**第四篇因版權問題 所以沒聲音
lady gaga《do  what u want》在各大音樂平台下架／並拒絕了參與r. kelly紀錄片訪問
最終決定將2013年與r. kelly合作的歌曲
勞凱利因涉嫌囚禁六名女子，控制她們任何生活作息，還包括衣著及如何進行性行為...而現在再度登上各大媒體版面。這些受害者聲稱r.kelly犯下強姦，虐待未成年女性超過二十年。 
其次連拍攝mv的導演也出現爭議
根據時代(time)雜誌的報導，音樂錄影帶的導演terry richardson
被指控近30年來拍攝性騷擾不斷眾多爭議導致該mv從未發布過，但mv中曝光的場景令人覺得不妥。
.
gaga在2016年第88屆奧斯卡舞台上演唱「till it happens to you」(親身經歷)
勇敢唱出性侵受傷者痛苦又心碎的感受，而她也邀請50位曾遭受性侵的受害者們同台合唱
有些人手臂上更寫著「not your fault」(不是你的錯)，希望透過歌曲傳遞最溫暖又勇敢的力量。儘管卡卡最終未能抱回獎項，但這段精彩表演也打動台下諸多嘉賓們，也被讚賞為當日最震撼人心的演出。
#tillthappenstoyou #dowhatuwant #metoo
.
gaga在twitter的聲明中：
女神卡卡：「我1000%是站在這些女孩們身邊的，我相信他們並了解他們身處痛苦當中，也深信她們希望曝光的事情該被大眾知道。我所聽到那些對於 r kelly 的指控是非常嚴重也讓人無可替他辯解。
同樣身為性侵受害者的我卻在我人生低潮中製作了這首歌也拍了音樂錄影帶，我的用意是要製作一首非常挑釁和煽動的作品，因為我非常的生氣也尚未走出我所遭遇的創傷。
當時那首歌叫做「do what u want」，很明顯的當時我的心態是非常扭曲的。如果我能回到過去並與當時的自己聊聊天，我會告訴年輕的我去接受專業的治療，就能理解我當時所患有的創傷後壓力症候群所帶來的影響。或是當我無法接受到正當的治療時應該去尋求幫助，並且公開並誠實的去訴說我所遇到的事情。
我無法回到過去，但是我可以繼續向前並且支持所有男生、女生、各種不同性取向以及各種不同種族的性侵受害者。我已多次透過我的事業來表態我對這樣的事情的立場，我發布這個聲明並非要找藉口，而是對這件事情的解釋。直到你身歷其境，你不會懂那種感受，但是我現在是知道這種感受的。
我將會把這首歌從 itunes 以及所有串流軟體下架並且再也不會與他合作。我對於我在年輕時所做的錯誤決定以及沒即時表態感到非常抱歉。我愛你們。」
name: 𝔄𝔩𝔳𝔞 𝔅𝔯𝔦𝔞𝔫 Western Music

text:
lady gaga and r. kelly have performed together several times since 2013. 
in the past, lady gaga has defended her decision to work with r. kelly by saying that she too has had plenty of false stories written about her during her career. at the time, the pop star was giving kellz the benefit of the doubt. now, with dozens of women accusing him of sexual misconduct, it’s become pretty clear to her that she needed to speak out to protect her own image.

many artists have denounced r. kelly since the lifetime docu-series surviving r. kelly aired over the weekend and finally, lady gaga has issued an apology for her previous collaboration with the singer. in addition to her apology, she vowed to remove their collaboration, “do what u want,” from itunes and streaming services. her statement reads: “as a victim of sexual assault myself, i made both the song and the video at a dark time in my life, my intention was to create something extremely defiant and provocative because i was angry and still hadn’t processed the trauma that had occurred in my own life. the song is called ‘do what u want (with my body),’ i think it’s clear how explicitly twisted my thinking was at the time.” she ends the message by apologizing for not speaking sooner and for her poor judgment. gaga has been vocal about her experiences with sexual assault and she actively works with survivors to share her own story. read her full statement in the full story at www.itskenbarbie.com (or swipe) what do you guys think about gaga removing the song from outlets? #rkelly #robertkelly #survivingrkelly #lifetime #lifetimetv #trappedinthecloset #metoo #muterkelly #ladygaga #gaga #astarisborn #astarisbornmovie #ladygaganews #monsters #littlemonsters #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #gossip

many aists have denounced r. kelly since the lifetime docu-series surviving r. kelly aired over the weekend and finally, lady gaga has issued an apology for her previous collaboration with the singer. in addition to her apology, she vowed to remove their collaboration, “do what u want,” from itunes and streaming services. her statement reads: “as a victim of sexual assault myself, i made both the song and the video at a dark time in my life, my intention was to create something extremely defiant and provocative because i was angry and still hadn’t processed the trauma that had occurred in my own life. the song is called ‘do what u want (with my body),’ i think it’s clear how explicitly twisted my thinking was at the time.” she ends the message by apologizing for not speaking sooner and for her poor judgment. gaga has been vocal about her experiences with sexual assault and she actively works with survivors to share her own story. read her full statement in the full story at www.itskenbarbie.com (or swipe) what do you guys think about gaga removing the song from outlets?

text:
"dann gehe ich nach unten und verziehe meinen mund zu einem lächeln, damit ich normal aussehe. es ist wichtig, dass ich normal aussehe. es ist wichtig, dass ich wie ein anständiges mädchen aussehe."
_________________________________________________
emma ist eine wunderschöne, junge frau und das ist ihr selbst auch sehr bewusst! sie ist überzeugt von sich, hat einige freunde, die sie bewundern und zu ihr und ihrem charakter aufschauen.
an einem abend ist eine party, sie sieht heiß aus. zu heiß, sagen viele. und dann sind da vier jungs und sie in einem schlafzimmer. und tabletten. und alkohol. am nächsten tag wacht sie auf und es ist nichts mehr so, wie es war. sie kann sich an nichts erinnern. es tauchen videos und fotos auf, "nacktes fleisch". will sie sich vielleicht nicht erinnern, weil alle sagen, dass sie es verdient hat, so wie sie rumläuft? dass sie es doch eigentlich wollte?

alsooo, schwieriges jugendbuch. erst mal das positive: das buch ist in vor der vergewaltigung und ein jahr danach aufgeteilt. das jahr danach bringt einen guten einblick in das überleben von vergewaltigungsopfern. der zweite teil hat mich also wesentlich mehr überzeugen können. 
die hauptperson emma ist im ersten teil allerdings so naiv und so komplett bescheuert, sie verhält sich gegenüber jedem wie das letzte arschloch. das war etwas unlogisch, hat mich genervt und dazu geführt, dass das buch anstrengend war und ich mich immer aufraffen musste, es weiter zu lesen.
es gibt bessere bücher zu dem thema, aber trotzdem ist es nach wie vor sehr wichtig, es anzusprechen und darzubringen! @carlsenverlag

text:
a recent study has found that sexual harassment and sexual assault are significantly associated with worse health indicators.
🧬
full article @
www.clearvuehealth.com/sahealth
🧬
sexual harassment is not only harmful mentally, but also may lead to medical consequences as well, particularly high blood pressure.
🧬
the cdc continues to find high a high prevalence of sexual assault against both men and women.
🧬
researchers from the university of pittsburgh studied a group of 304 middle aged women to see whether sexual harassment and sexual assault were significantly correlated to health indicators and outcomes.
🧬
22% of the patients in the study had reported a history of sexual assault.
researchers estimated that these patients had nearly triple the risk of depression compared to women without a history of sexual harassment, and more the double the risk of anxiety and poor sleep. all three effects were highly statistically significant.
🧬
this study found that workplace sexual harassment also leads to real health issues.
🧬
they found that 19% of the patients reported a history of workplace sexual harassment. these patients had a significantly higher prevalence of sleep issues and high blood pressure.
🧬
according to the cdc, approximately 44% of american women have experienced some type of sexual violence. this includes unwanted sexual contact, rape attempts, sexual coercion, and/or penetration.
🧬
if further research confirms that sexual assault doubles or triples a person's risk of depression, anxiety, and poor sleep, then it's plausible that a significant portion of the mental health burden we have in our society today can attributed to sexual violence.
🧬
a significant number of men also had experienced some type of sexual violence. while the proportion is lower at 25% vs 44% in women, it certainly warrants further study into the effects of #sexualassault in men.
🧬
#healthfacts #healthtips #publichealth #primarycare #healtheducation #data #dataisbeautiful #dataviz #medicine #health #science #healthcare #design #medicalscience #healthscience #medicalstudent 
#mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #depressionawareness

text:
the awesome card i received from old co-workers in the mail yesterday! it’s amazing to me the number of people, (dozens of which i don’t even know) who have reached out to me since coming forward about the abuse i endured and sharing my story. it has shown me a few things but most importantly that my work in helping others is just beginning. there are so many women out there that have endured their own version of what i did, many of whom never have been able to use their voice to fight for themselves and the love and justice they deserve. i have faith that we can change that together. i’ve also realized that there are a few out there that are going to continue to degrade and fight me for finally coming forward. 30+ year old bullies that find it important to tear me down for stripping their friends facade. what’s even more important than that handful though is all the love, support and encouragement i’ve received from the many handfuls behind and beside me. i will continue to rise. 
#appreciationpost #survivor #victor #enddomesticviolence #metoo #myjourney #speakyourtruth #warrior #blogger #thankful #peace #healing #strength #rebuild #instagood

text:
изображая жертву моды: джованна батталья 
энгельберт о моде и себе.
стилист, fashion-редактор, креативный директор, автор книги и жена магната, джованна батталья энгельберт к моде относится серьезно, а к себе – с юмором. 
высокая волоокая брюнетка из обеспеченной и богемной миланской семьи пытается работать моделью, но оказывается слишком принципиальной, чтобы быть пластилином в чужих руках. она решает самостоятельно создавать «модные миры» и становится стилистом – сначала работает для независимых журналов, вкладывая в съемки все заработанные моделингом деньги, потом знакомится с анной делло руссо и франкой соццани, начинает стилизовать съемки для изданий condé nast, а через несколько лет становится приглашенным редактором американского w и японского vogue. тогда же она знакомится со сказочно красивым и сказочно богатым блондином-девелопером родом из швеции и выходит за него замуж.
ее зовут джованна батталья, ей 38, и она на самом деле существует. ее пиар-агент несколько раз переносит интервью, в итоге я звоню в час дня по стокгольму и застаю джованну за редким занятием: она сидит за ноутбуком и занимается рутинной работой. у нее сильный и очаровательный итальянский акцент и громкий голос – даже не видя ее, представляешь, как она красочно машет руками, когда говорит: «думаешь, я назову имена своих клиентов и раскрою все тонкости своей работы? нет. скажем так: то, что я делаю, называется creative direction. я помогаю брендам выстроить имидж и найти новые методы коммуникации. нет универсальных рецептов успеха, как и табу. главное – концентрироваться на продукте, не застывать во времени, привлекать внимание и новую аудиторию

text: last august i attended the global lean in regional leaders conference in california. i met some amazing women who spoke and encouraged us to continue on our journey for gender equality in the workplace. joanne lipman was one of those dynamic speakers. i immediately knew i had to have her on the show. not only is a powerhouse woman but she is also an encourager and an advocate for women in the workplace. her list of accomplishment is a mile long, including the wall street journal, cco of gannett and so much more. she was also the editor in chief of usa today and is now the author of the book, that's what she said: what men need to know (and women need to tell them) about working together. joanne and i talk about those discussions that we all need to be having with the men we work with. conversations that need to take place about the #metoo topic and how we, as women, can move into a better place of equality. it was a great chat filled with lots of great advice and insights from this fabulous leader. joanne and i also talked about her book club, her best business advice from her former boss and we even talked about her favorite seasonal snack! #linktolisteninbio
name: Corine Sandifer

text:
i have a break between classes on tuesday, i decided to go to the library because that’s where a bookworm would go. i found this gem in their new arrivals, i read a chapter and couldn’t stop. i promised myself that my goal for 2019 was to read books that are intentional and i’m off to a good start. it’s so common to hide behind ourselves and build a wall while cutting off everyone around us when something bad happens to us; we should speak and point out all the things that are wrong in our cultures that make us feel like we shouldn't speak out about sexual assault. we have gained some pathway in the states with the #metoo movement, but other countries are still struggling with this on a high level.
•
•
•mumbai. indignant at the silence on the issue in india, she wrote an article for an indian women’s magazine questioning how we perceive rape and rape victims. thirty years later her story went viral in the wake of the 2012 fatal gang rape in delhi and the global outcry that followed. in 2013, abdulali published an op-ed in the new york times called “after being raped, i was wounded; my honor wasn’t” that was widely circulated.

#intentionalbooks #bookstagram #bookish #bookphotography #bookishfeature #womenempowerment #booktography #rapeculture

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
we owe black girls better than what we’ve given.
we also owe black women better than what we’ve given.
these words by our friend @seed_of_the_free_llc suffice to sit alone. but in the wake of surviving r.kelly, we also need to talk about this specific context in which so many black girls were harmed, and their harm ignored by individuals, communities, and systems for decades. we need to talk about how we universally ignore the pain of black girls and women. how we disbelieve and silence black girls and women. we need to talk about our individual and collective roles in trusting, valuing, and supporting black girls and women. 
we do better for black girls when we center black voices and support black advocates and organizers. we do better for black girls when we challenge (fix, burn down) the systems that were never built to support black girls. we have a responsibility to do better. 
@seed_of_the_free_llc offered critical commentary after watching #survivingrkelly —
“the victim blaming and sex shaming tactics of “fast girls deserve what they get” makes me wonder who hurt you or left you behind to make the cries of black girls foreign or suspicious to your ears? ...we owe black girls better than what we’ve given.” go to her profile to see more. #muterkelly

text:
“how do you feel your birth went?”
⠀
one of the many student midwives who’d practiced cervical checks on me sat stiffly next to me on the postpartum ward bed. i wanted to spit on her.
⠀
“it was great.” i said coldly, holding my small, 2 day old baby closer.
⠀⠀
her eyes darted downwards, presumably towards the papers in her hands, but i’d like to think that for a split second she felt some type of guilt or remorse.
⠀
“so what are you going to do to stop this from ever happening again?” she said catching my eyes once more.
⠀
that’s the moment i got it. i understood. the things done to me weren’t necessary or even accidental, they were retaliative. they were retaliative because of the money they lost when i refused unnecessary procedures and testing.
⠀
they were retaliative because i didn’t trust them after they misdiagnosed me 3 times, and i told them.
⠀
why did i tell them?
⠀
“oh excuse me — i mean, what birth control are we setting you up with?”
⠀
the next 30 minutes were spent listening to the girl drone on about her pseudo cycle pills and implants. after her spill i smiled and told her i was good.
⠀
then she told me that i would be pregnant again in the next year because ovulating women, “get too caught in the moment to remember protection”.
⠀
i don’t think i’ll ever forget how absolutely atrocious her presence in that room was.
⠀
#metoo
#mybirthtoo

text:
.
i always always, get caught up in whether or not i should have expressed a certain feeling to someone bc maybe they won’t understand where i’m coming from. . 
or maybe i said too much and they think i’m over thinking it, .
or maybe i shouldn’t have said i love you to that co-worker bc we just work together, or my friends mom, bc she’s not my friend, her daughter is,
.
or maybe i shouldn’t have called this person my best friend, what if they don’t feel the same, they already have a best friend, .
or maybe i shouldn’t have told this person i needed space because now we hardly talk at all. .
but honestly, that’s fine. because regardless, i still expressed my heart’s true feelings and if i don’t own them, they will go unaccounted for, or worse, i’ll give someone else the right to control my emotions or feelings. .
so know the story of your heart by owning those feelings. it’s your story for a reason.
name: Child Of Indigo
tweet_full:
.
i always always, get caught up in whether or not i should have expressed a certain feeling to someone bc maybe they won’t understand where i’m coming from. . 
or maybe i said too much and they think i’m over thinking it, .
or maybe i shouldn’t have said i love you to that co-worker bc we just work together, or my friends mom, bc she’s not my friend, her daughter is,
.
or maybe i shouldn’t have called this person my best friend, what if they don’t feel the same, they already have a best friend, .
or maybe i shouldn’t have told this person i needed space because now we hardly talk at all. .
but honestly, that’s fine. because regardless, i still expressed my heart’s true feelings and if i don’t own them, they will go unaccounted for, or worse, i’ll give someone else the right to control my emotions or feelings. .
so know the story of your heart by owning those feelings. it’s your story for a reason.

text: you set the stage for how others treat you. i have a tendency to care too much for others feelings and making sure they are 'okay' before caring about how i feel about a situation.. i will give you the shirt off my back before i would ever ask why you need it.... and then you extend that offer else where, in all directions before looking back at yourself. what i never really realized in life is that more than not, that person will be grateful and thankful... but then you have those others who will suck the life out of you and because you are who you are... you won't realize it until its too late. then you're left wondering wtf you did wrong. don't take this as a don't be kind, be heartless, and cold. what i'm saying is fill your cup first and take no shit! limit yourself to how much you give, know your limits. its okay to cancel plans and to say no. its okay to tell a friend or family member that they're being a dick and you need to breathe for a moment. its okay to take care yourself, fully, before caring about any other! ♥

text:
trigger warning: sexual abuse 
it had been a few days that we shifted back home, i didn’t know . i was just excited about finally having more people to play with. you were one of them, keeping us happy with monopoly and getting us ice cream every now and then. 
so when you suggested to a bunch of little kids to play hide and seek i didn’t see a problem. i didn’t see the problem when i was pressed against a bookshelf with your hand covering my mouth and your hand travelling up by ass, you asking me “breathe.” and i couldn’t. 
i was 9 years old, you were 19. i didn’t see the problem then. and that’s why it happened, again and again and again. 
when i saw the problem i was 12, i had gotten my period and when you tried that shit again, i bolted away. it haunted me, every night being choked with your disgusting body pressed against mine was my worst nightmare. and it turned exactly that. for 5 years, i didn’t tell anyone. i slept every night with demons in my head, i woke up screaming, broken and helpless. i hated feeling that way. 
so when i was 17, i told it to my parents. my mom fired up with anger and my dad had a tear escape his eye. i thought i’d be safe but what he told later shook me to my core. “i’ll tell you something, boys have urges.” he said, “and sometimes you might become the victim of it. and now you can’t do anything about it.” that’s when i had my first encounter with anxiety.
#metoo

text:
#novedad 
tres acontecimientos más una sentencia (el #metoo, la carta de las intelectuales francesas, la huelga feminista del 8 de marzo y la sentencia de la manada) han marcado la agenda en los últimos meses y han puesto en el punto de mira el concepto del feminismo hoy. marta sanz reflexiona acerca de lo que ello supone, cómo posicionarse ante esos hechos concretos, cómo «proteger» la lucha feminista de la simplificación y comercialización de un capitalismo que lo puede absorber todo, y piensa también sobre las cuotas y el poder, para llegar a la conclusión de que quizás lo que deba modificarse sea la noción de poder misma... una reflexión de una mujer que se pregunta, en sus actuaciones públicas y privadas, en cada gesto y cada palabra, cuál es el camino hacia la igualdad.

#genero #feminismo 
@anagramaeditor en #elespejolibros

text:
the psychological process of dissociation is the process of separating or detaching mentally from something that can be physically or emotionally distressing. ⁣
⁣
we have all heard people who have experienced something traumatic say something like, “i felt like i was outside of myself,” or “i was watching myself.”⁣
⁣
someone in a dissociative state can cause people one to lose memory, consciousness, and in extreme cases take assume a whole other identity (although this is super rare). ⁣
⁣
in this episode of @blacktherapistpodcast, our host @msnikbanks discusses the ability of the brain to shut down psychologically when a person’s emotional or physical discomfort becomes too great. ⁣
⁣
when you grow up in a community and environment of trauma, and abuse, for many of us this becomes a way to cope with everyday life. while this can happen for in everyday occurrences naturally. ⁣
⁣
we know people who have experienced trauma who do this to themselves through the use of sex, people and even substances. ⁣
⁣
in this episode, we talk about the environment that creates sexual predators like r kelly and how communities of color can be a breeding ground for those who want to harm vulnerable women and girls. ⁣
⁣

text:
and she’s still the strongest woman i know.

trapped

she’s six years old
she’s in a bath
playing with toys
making a splash
uncle walks in
girl closes thighs
he came to prey 
it’s in his eyes
girl begs and pleads
“leave me alone”
he shuts her up
he’s in the zone
“get out right now 
don’t want you here
can wash myself”
then falls the tears
beast touches girl
she kicks and screams
“what’s wrong with you?
don’t be so mean.”
decades have past 
and sadly so
the girl inside
never did grow -alexasym

text:
a 35 ans, après sept mois d’allaitement, la course à la cinquantaine a commencé . cheveux courts travaillés tous les 2 mois, sport quotidien, vins nature, whiskys choisis. je vieillissais et la jeune cuisine naissait. j’ai nourri la bête des plus belles assiettes, j’ai huilé d’olive ma peau normande nourrie au beurre. j’ai affiné le grain avec les noyaux. j’ai glissé en moi le meilleur gras maturé. j’ai ciselé mon regard sur les plus beaux chefs. ma langue, précise et fouineuse, a des gouts inédits. j’ai musclé mes organes à force de mâcher. je bois nature et vis mature. j’ai construit ma ligne dorsale avec ma ligne éditoriale. je transpire des odeurs de cuisine exquise. je me parfume de fumets et fume de jolis mets.
comment je suis à 50 ans ? qu’est ce que je fais en 2019 ? a quoi je ressemble ? pour sûr, pas à mes 25 ans. j’aime un homme de 50 et aussi regarder ceux de 25. je m’habille uni et serré. je slim encore. je mets des talons et bouffe le jambon. je mange grébaut et plus plus ginette mathiot. plus de rides oui, mais plus de rigueur. ce corps là… je l’ai choisi, nourri, travaillé, transporté, observé, bousculé, visité, donné. et toi yann moix , qu’as-tu fait de ton corps pour plaire aux 25 ans ? •
—💪🏻—
•
#femme #50ans #yannmoixlesfemmesde50anstemmerdent #yannmoix @septimeparis #polemique @wolinskiki @colombeschneck @sophiefontanel

text:
this is gonna be dope, people.
-
@cheftaylorbarry and i are beyond excited for tonight and the inaugural meeting of @culinarycommons!
-
join us @ovenly studio one54 in greenpoint at 6:30pm with @outsmartnyc for our first workshop on understanding sexual violence, supporting survivors and accessing resources. our industry, like so many, has not been held accountable, there’s been no support, and it’s time for that to change.
-
we are grateful to be supported by @goodcompanyzine and we’ll have copies for everyone! thank you @designsponge and @alliemisch 💕. we cannot say thank you enough to @agathakulaga,  @erinpatinkin and the @ovenly team for welcoming us into their space and giving our first meeting a home. we are beyond grateful to the people of @outsmartnyc who are making it their mission to end sexual violence in nyc, raise awareness and provide resources. support them if you can! and my partner in this project @cheftaylorbarry. you are 💯.
-
this event is free and open to all. our goal is to offer monthly speakers and workshops for hospitality professionals and hopefully make our industry a better place to work and thrive. come say hi and let us know what you want to hear and see from us. it’s about you.
-
we are taking submissions for speakers, venues and collaborations so please get in touch 💕!

text:
„twitter ist, wie kein anderes digitales medium so aggressiv und in keinem anderen medium gibt es so viel #hass, böswilligkeit und #hetze. offenbar triggert twitter in mir etwas an: aggressiver, lauter, polemischer und zugespitzter zu sein – und das alles in einer schnelligkeit, die es schwer macht, dem nachdenken raum zu lassen. offenbar bin ich nicht immun dagegen.“ so hat robert #habeck seinen rückzug aus den sozialen medien begründet. ist hass im #netz ein plattform-bezogenes problem, und ist der digitale rückzug der einzig sinnvolle umgang damit? 
seit langem müssen insbesondere betroffene von #rassismus, #sexismus und anderer #diskriminierung die erfahrung machen, dass das internet voller hass ist: verleumdung, morddrohungen, selbstmordaufrufe oder die androhung von #gewalt gehören zum alltag derer, die sich auf facebook, twitter & co. zu umstrittenen themen wie #metoo oder #metwo äußern. die gespaltene gesellschaft tobt sich zunehmend online aus. hassbotschaften wie „lösch dich“ und vergewaltigungsfantasien werden zunehmend unter klarnamen verschickt. all das wirkt sich auf das sicherheitsgefühl im „echten“ leben aus.

bei unserer veranstaltung #löschdich wollen wir mit netz-aktivist*innen diskutieren, wie betroffene mit hatespeech umgehen: was tun die sozialen netzwerke gegen trolle und stalker? wie funktioniert das netzdg? und wie kann digitale zivilcourage konkret aussehen?

podium mit: ▶️ ali can (initiator von #metwo) ▶️ ayesha khan (netz-aktivistin und freie autorin),
▶️ olivia sarma (leiterin von response. beratung für betroffene rechter und rassistischer gewalt) ▶️ nava zarabian (jugendschutz.net).
▶️ moderation: pola sarah nathusius (journalistin, hessischer rundfunk). dienstag, 22. januar 2019, 20.00 uhr

vai planeta!!! que exemplo lindo, né?! numa onda mundial de fechamento de fronteiras e de ódio à outras culturas, esta reportagem nos faz lembrar de que ainda existem seres humanos que reconhecem outros seres humanos, independente de cultura, etnia, crenças e etc.

seres humanos, apenas!

torço muito para que este exemplo seja seguido por mais pessoas.

reconhecer a dificuldade alheia, sem julgar, sem discriminar, mas sim com o olhar de ajuda e acolhimento, é o que nosso país precisa.

se você já é essa pessoa, está de parabéns!!! saiba que isso faz a diferença para as pessoas ao seu redor.

se não consegue ser esta pessoa ou se sofre com as críticas, não consegue se desvencilhar de relações assim, saiba que pode contar comigo!

melhoras também são feitas com pequenas mudanças!

text:
in the end of last year i illustrated an article for anmesty international about self-determination. the article was written by marie kajava and you can read it on amnesty finland’s website.

in the illustrations i highlighted the three main issues surrounding self-determination. 
the right to your gender identity and rightful gender markers and the right to get your desired treatment to fit your transition. stopping forced surgery on intersex children and letting them choose themselves if they wish to have surgery to allign with their gender identity. and the right to choose over your body, who touches it, when and how. 
it was an honor to illustrate this article on this very important topic.

text:
even if survivors choose to report sexual assaults, justice is not always served. out of every 1,000 rapes, 994 perpetrators will walk free.

_____
"if i am someone who believes there is going to be retaliation, or the person who committed and perpetrated the events against me is well-respected, has a high-profile within a community, a community i care about, i am going to see a lot of risk related to reporting, particularly because it will instigate an investigation, and that might be a risk i'm not willing to take," - keeli sorensen

#nomore #breakingthesilence #timesup #metoo #supportingsurvivors #whyididntreport

text:
har lavet endnu en lang story om det vigtige emne psykisk vold. .
.
@mettehelena lagde en barsk, men oplysende story op, forleden om hvordan psykisk vold ser ud i praksis, med en masse screenshots fra en mand som både stalkede og truede sin ekskone med voldtægt. .
.
jeg har fra tid til anden kvinder i min praksis, som har været i psykisk voldelig forhold, eller har været udsat for overgreb og voldtægt. 
det er et emne jeg brænder ufattelig meget for, og som virkelig kan få mig op af stolen, fordi der er så meget uretfærdighed forbundet med det, ift. at den udøvende ikke bliver dømt.

det kan man så forhåbentlig snart. i det korte klip her, kommer jeg til at sige, at man kan blive dømt for det nu. det er måske ikke helt korrekt juridisk set, men du forstår budskabet. .
.
se med på min story (den bliver også et fast højdepunkt) og bliv klogere ❤️ og send en kærlig tanke til de kvinder, børn og og mænd, der lever i det her helvede hver eneste dag. de har brug for det ❤️

text:
if you can relate to this, you're not the only one. we were fooled by our abusers as well. please don't spend all your time replaying those early moments in your head. we know firsthand how tempting it is to do so.⠀
⠀
you were fooled. ⠀
you were deceived.⠀
you were an act in a master manipulator's circus.⠀
you're not alone.⠀
⠀
and if you can't relate, know that so many survivors of physical/emotional/psychological abuse did not know at the beginning that "the storm was coming". questions like, "didn't you see..." or "why didn't you just walk away..." do nothing but further traumatize. ⠀
⠀

text:
in october 2018 i ended a 4 year long abusive relationship. my life changed drastically in a 1000 ways. some negative. some positive. all for a reason. my new years resolution is to talk about it. i have been too scared, embarrassed and forbidden to do that. i want to share my story and hear yours. i want to help others heal while also healing myself. i want to live my life freely. time is precious. don’t waste it with the wrong people. 
#notallmen #yesallwomen #domesticviolenceawareness #womenempoweringwomen

text:
review:
colette (directed by wash westmoreland, 2018)
all throughout history, women have had to fight hard to have the same recognition as men as intellectually equal human beings capable of revolutionising the world of science, technologies, and humanities. in this beautifully crafted inspiring story, we follow the early life of colette, one of the most prolific french female writers of all time. this isn't a film that breaks any new ground in terms of its storytelling, it's a fairly traditional period biopic, however, it does break new ground in the way it brings such a groundbreaking figure to the big screen and tells us not only an empowering female story, but also an empowering lgbtq story, about a woman who fought and defied all gender norms imposed on her. keira knightley is absolutely incredible as the title character and breaths such depth into this unique historical figure, in this story of a woman who breaks the chains put on her by a male-dominated society that imposes itself on her and who fights against a possessive husband who is more concerned about profiting from her talent and gaining fame than giving her any real freedom or recognition. this film portrays with such compassion the story of this incredible woman who was able to overcome the pressures of patriarchy and establish herself as her own independent individual woman. this is a story that was not only important back then, but it's still very much important in this era of #metoo, where women are still fighting to be recognised as as much capable artists as men. this is a well-crafted, beautifully filmed movie that you should definitely check out.

#newpost: j’ai écris ce nouvel article intitulé « nous devons protéger nos hommes » suite à la diffusion du documentaire « surviving r. kelly » et les commentaires que j’ai pu lire qui exhortent les femmes noires à soutenir les hommes noirs à n’importe quel prix. dans cet article, j’explique pourquoi cette posture est dangereuse et qu’il faut qu’on arrête de sacrifier l’intégrité et la liberté des jeunes filles et femmes noires aux profit de criminels et de prédateurs sexuels, même s’ils font partie de nos communautés. aux filles et femmes noires, je vous dis : « le silence ne vous protègera pas. il protégera personne excepté votre bourreau. nos vies valent bien plus que la réputation ou l’image des hommes noirs ». c’est une conversation importante que nous devons avoir au sein de nos communautés pour briser la loi du silence sur les violences sexuelles. 
#yoursilencewillnotprotectyou #feminism #blackgirlsmatter #blackwomenlivesmatter #sayhername #timesup #muterkelly #metoo

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
after watching the #survivingrkelly documentary, i was horrified and unfortunately not just because of the stories of survivors but also because the unbelievable amount of victim shaming i saw in comments on posts online, accusing these women who were underage children, at the time of the alleged abuse, as "cheque-collecting wanna-be's who knew exactly what they were getting themselves into" and although my message to these trolls may never reach them, today i stand in solidarity to each and every victim of abuse and predators, of any age, worldwide who are suffering in silence or speaking out to end the shame. i also stand in solidarity to @taranajaneen who started the #metoo movement and campaigns and organisations who provide support to survivors... ❤️
•
unfortunately, in the midst of all the disbelief, victim shaming and trolling towards these women, so many supporters of the #muterkelly movement are also being dragged for "jumping on the wagon" or "not giving a fuck sooner" and i just wanna let you know that it's never to late to create and support change! 💪
•

text: “trauma, by definition, is unbearable and intolerable. it produces physiological changes, including a recalibration of the brain’s alarm system, an increase in stress hormones activity , and alterations in the system that filters relevant informations from irrelevant. we now know that trauma compromises the brain area that communicates the physical, embodied feeling of being alive. these changes explain why traumatized individuals become hypervigilant to threat at the expense of spontaneously engaging in their day-to-day lives. they also help us understand why traumatized people so often keep repeating the same problems and have such trouble learning from experience. we now know that their behaviours are not the result of moral failings or signs of lack of willpower or bad character—they are caused by actual changes in the brain.” #thebodykeepsthescore #besselvanderkolk #trauma #treatment

text:
hoy dibujé a bowie a partir de un esbozo que hice en un cacho de cartón. "tres años? ya?
aunque nunca te irás del todo, porque dejaste una huella de felicidad indeleble en millones de almas. 
el mundo se va a la mierda, starman. cada ve es más feo, gris, sucio, mezquino... por eso, y por tu música, por tu arte, y porque al fin y al cabo, cuando te fuiste, se fue un color entero.
te echamos de menos, @davidbowie 
y te recordamos, sea o no tu aniversario, cada puñetero día."
#missingbowie #bowie #davidbowie #davidrobertjones #davidbowieforever

drawing from an original sketch on carboard. "three years, really?
though you'll never be gone forever, because of the amazing gift of your music, your art, and the happiness it brought to millions of souls. 
but the world today is a sad, grey, nasty, ugly place to live today. 
and when you parted, a whole color was gone with you. 
we miss you, david bowie. 
every single fucking day of our lives."

text:
as a mom to a boy, this is a great reminder. "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys — and the document features a warning.
“traditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit males’ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,” the report warns.

the new “guidelines for psychological practice with boys and men” defines “masculinity ideology” as “a particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.” the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, “it’s ok to not be ok all the time.”'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
to all the survivors out there- i write this to you,

that you may find peace. 
because i held on too tightly of that pain and rage.

i hope you find strength to truly love yourself.

that you may center yourself and find happiness by fully and truly accepting  who you are- despite what happened.

i hope you can reach a place where you don’t need affirmation from others because you alone- are more than enough.

that you can be bold enough to forgive yourself.

be kind to yourself because you are doing everything that you can.

i hope you can keep moving, listen to your own voice because you have one.

and may your own voice move you to rise and lift off from the floor.

because the beauty of pain and darkness is the perseverance that makes you stronger.

and i tell you this, when you move on and let go.

and you free yourself from all of the rancor,

you will feel the sun again and it feels so damn good. 
because you survived,
because you are loved,
beautiful in all of your ways.

strong with dreams,
driven with goals,
filled with compassion. 
my love to you 💜❤️,
katrina lee .
.
.
@survivor.love.letter

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: i finished the surviving r kelly documentary last night and i am so shocked and outraged at how long this has gone on. my heart goes out to all the victims of his emotional and physical abuse and their families. this man is a predator that feeds of power and in my opinion is far worse than harvey weinstein and needs to be held accountable. i am not trying to compare the two, my point is, harvey is being investigated and r kelly is not. we have ourselves to blame in this situation, i knew of the allegations but failed to try and understand the severity of the situation. i still continued to listen to his music. stop separating art from the artist, just because he sings like an angel, doesn’t mean he is one. i still want to applaud @johnlegend@keke @vincestaples @chancetherapper@jadapinkettsmith @ladygaga for continuing the conversation. i really hope that more musicians stand up against this monster#muterkelly #metoo #blackgirlslivesmatter

text:
kogan maintains that everything he did was legal and he had a “close working relationship” with facebook, which had granted him permission for his apps.

cambridge analytica had its data. this was the foundation of everything it did next – how it extracted psychological insights from the “seeders” and then built an algorithm to profile millions more.

for more than a year, the reporting around what cambridge analytica did or didn’t do for trump has revolved around the question of “psychographics”, but wylie points out: “everything was built on the back of that data. the models, the algorithm. everything. why wouldn’t you use it in your biggest campaign ever?” in december 2015, the guardian’s harry davies published the first report about cambridge analytica acquiring facebook data and using it to support ted cruz in his campaign to be the us republican candidate. but it wasn’t until many months later that facebook took action. and then, all they did was write a letter. in august 2016, shortly before the us election, and two years after the breach took place, facebook’s lawyers wrote to wylie, who left cambridge analytica in 2014, and told him the data had been illicitly obtained and that “gsr was not authorised to share or sell it”. they said it must be deleted immediately.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
anchored in and inspired by the many voices of the #metoo movement, the group exhibition “mademoiselle” which brought together a generation of international women artists at the crac occitanie in sète closed its doors on 6 january 2019. exploring the issues and paradoxes of being a young woman today, and as curator tara londi explained, “the exhibition elaborates on contemporary prototypes of femininity, women’s oppression and suppression, social relationships, and a general sexualization of culture. it reflects upon pervasive models of ‘youthitude and femininitude’.”
-
ancrée et inspirée par les nombreuses voix du mouvement #metoo, l’exposition collective « mademoiselle », qui rassemblait une nouvelle génération de femmes artistes internationales au crac occitanie à sète, a fermé ses portes le 6 janvier 2019. explorant les enjeux et paradoxes liés à la féminité contemporaine, et comme l’explique la commissaire tara londi, « l’exposition développe les prototypes contemporains de la féminité, l’oppression des femmes et l’aliénation vécue dans leurs relations sociales, et la sexualisation générale de la culture. elle rebondit également sur les modèles en vigueur de la « jeunitude » et de la « féminitude ». »
-
image credit: zoë buckman, they don’t call me big, 2014. courtesy of the artist and gavlak los angeles/gavlak palm beach
-
@taralondi @crac_occitanie @zoebuckman #groupshow #contemporaryart #womenartists #metoo #feminism #mademoiselle #crac

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quaer-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, suppoing him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i am so pleased to have been invited to a meeting with devon and cornwall constabulary to speak with them about survivors experiences of using the police. 
i meet many survivors of domestic and sexual abuse who worry about the response they may get from agencies, especially the police. 
historical abuse where memories are fragmented, buried or hazy pose survivors with all sorts of worries about being believed and a lack of evidence.

i have had two very different experiences with police officers this week when chatting about my abuse.

one was empathetic, warm, professional and listened.

the other was harder, did not listen and made me feel like was wasting police time.
i challenged the attitude of the officer and they admitted that they weren't the 'touchy feely type'. horse's for courses and all that shenanigans, but really?? you come and see a victim of historical abuse and you're not touchy feely!! times need to change!! #underreported #underresourced #police #historicalabuse #trust #listeningskills #warmheart #metoo #sayitloud #campaigning #wontshutup
#speakoutsisterhood #timesup
#woman #mission #brave

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters
