text:
llevan toda la vida educándonos para ser competencia. así manteniendo los privilegios del heteropatriarcado mientras nos peleábamos entre nosotras.
siempre se decía que las mujeres “eran más malas que los hombres” o que “éramos peores entre nosotras”. es algo que muchas interiorizamos desde pequeñas hasta creérnoslo nosotras mismas. ¡imaginad todo lo que puede conseguir la educación! 
ahora, tras tantas injusticias y más acceso a la información gracias a las nuevas tecnologías, una nueva oleada feminista ha llegado de nuevo y se han acabado esas creencias de que somos enemigas para unirnos más que nunca. ya no somos compañeras, somos amigas, nos llamamos hermanas. 
desde que me abrí esta cuenta de instagram he ido conociendo a mujeres de todos lugares del mundo que han leído mis palabras en esta red social, me han apoyado y las he sentido tan cerca que parece que nos conocemos desde siempre. 
se ha terminado la era del terror, no vamos a vivir con miedo, vamos a luchar juntas. desde todas partes del mundo, dadas de la mano, ante la violencia machista. en la ciudad en la que vivo he sentido el respaldo y el apoyo de todos los rincones de españa en cada huelga, cada manifestación, concentración... pero os juro que no sabéis lo hermoso que es sentir el apoyo desde otros continentes a los que “no les afectan” las injusticias de españa. 
y las entiendo, porque cuando leo noticias de otros lugares del mundo en los que sufren mujeres solo suena en mi cabeza la palabra sororidad y me entran ganas de coger un vuelo para abrazar a todas aquellas que ahora ya son mis hermanas. #hermanayositecreo #entretodas #sororidad #yotecreo

*

text:
punk rock? we need to talk. .
. like most people in the early glam and punk scene, david bowie used his fame , power,  and access to drugs that lower sexual inhibitions to prey on at least one adolescent girl. #iggypop wrote a song about 13 year old sable starr leaving him for #johnnythunders. #jagger , #jimmypage ... it's all of them. sexual predators are the rule in rock and roll, not the exception. .
.
 these men who so define rebellion have never done all that much of it when you really think about it. using drugs, money, and celebrity to have sex with inherently vulnerable people is the status quo.
.
.
i came of age as a female in a punk scene. i was queer and looking for people as weird as i felt. what i found was decent music, a set of ethics that seemed to align with my own thoughts about society, and people angry at things i was angry about. i was also introduced to drugs and sexual violence, two things that went on to define my young adulthood. .
.
in these spaces i frequently interacted with men much older than me who,  looking back, had no business hanging out with adolescents. they werent cool. they weren't punk rock. they were losers who used drugs and street cred as currency for the admiration of children. they were predators. we were children. .
.
if i could define punk as a culture i would call it hypocritical and devoid of the very ethics it subscribes to. it's rebel-adjacent patriarchal bullshit and no place for an actual anarchist . it's a mirage beyond which a lot of irreparable damage has been done at the expense of vulnerable people -- people with 2,000 times more potential for creativity and rebellion than the washed-up drunks and j*nkies, these punx larpers who hold all the laud, the esteem but none of the conviction, none of the heart, with brains long since pickled.
.
.
i guess u could say over the past few years i have pulled away from the scene i once defined myself by, as embarassing as that is to say at 31. honestly, it was never genuine; i was always a million times too real/objectively badass for a scene rife with wet-brained, hedonistic posers lol
.
2 punx 4 punx, i suppose. it's not me -- it's you.
. 🤘👋✌
#oldhead
#recovery

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
diversity and inclusion isn’t just an issue for large-scale corporate organisations or for those who can afford to employ a diversity manager. it is a mindset and underpins the culture of your organisation, no matter the size.
our third top tip to implementing a strategy is:
monitor, monitor, monitor
look around you. does your organisation reflect the world outside and most importantly the world in which your customers live?
organisations that mirror the customers they serve have a greater understanding of their wants and needs and therefore are more efficient and effective in developing successful products and services.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text: in 2018 i applied •“be the response you want to receive”• to all aspects of my life. it helped me grow in ways i could never have imagined, not just my communication.  now in 2019, i feel i have given this advice to too many already. not a clap back, but not spreading yourself so thin for everyone else, til there’s nothing left for you. acknowledging a learning experience for what it is.  this man also had 20 one liners, that toasted! 🥂🥂 if they aren’t supportin then they shouldn’t be important. i hope a girl sees this tonight, and she remembers it’s truth.

text:
the word of the year 2018 
hey, guys! 
каждый год самые известные словари публикуют слова, которые были самыми употребляемыми за прошедший год. анализ происходит не только по количеству раз, вбиваемого в онлайн словарь определённого слова, но и по анализу употребления в заголовках газет, комментариях и вообще определения данного слова как культурно- значимого.
.
annnnnnd.... the word of the year 2018 is....toxic!
the adjective toxic is defined as «poisonous». 🤔
.
why was toxic chosen as word of the year?
the oxford dictionary data shows that, along with a 45% rise in the number of times it has been looked up on dictionaries over the last year the word toxic has been used in an array of contexts, both in its literal and more metaphorical senses.
.
top 10 «toxic» collocates in 2018
by absolute frequency
📌 	chemical
📌 masculinity
📌 substance
📌 gas
📌 environment
📌 relationship
📌 culture
📌 waste
📌	algae
📌 air
.
this year toxic chemical has had particular significance as the nerve agent poisoning ( нервно-паралитический газ). ongoing international attention to the case, where former russian office and his daughter were attacked, including rising concern over who has access to the world’s toxic chemical stockpiles, ensured that ‘chemical’ topped the list of words most frequently seen alongside toxic in 2018.
.
similarly literal and deadly are toxic substance, toxic gas, and toxic waste, with the latter especially becoming a focal point as the us seeks to combat the spread of toxic waste in the wake of hurricanes and people speak out against businesses burning toxic waste, notably in india.
.
this burning of toxic waste, resulting in the release of toxic gases, has been identified as one of a number of causes of toxic air. air pollution has rapidly become a prime public health concern, and global attention reached a high in october 2018 when the world health organization published its report into the quality of air breathed by children worldwide.
.
the term toxic environment itself, however, has been more frequently used in reference to harmful workplace environment.

text: i have retroactively decided to post one thing a day to my ig page because i would like to be a little better at small consistant habits for appreciating my days. fortunately i only decided to do this a few days late into january. i am not usually a new years resolution type of person, but 2018 was a year of a tremendous changes and i expect 2019 will be in also  change me in ways i haven't even considered yet. so it feels like an appropriate moment to cultivate a small habit.  in the spirit of catch up and also thinking about photos with a lot of story to tell: these headshots were taken by the vancouver tourism board in san jose a few months ago. this year american anthropological association was held in san jose in the middle of the wildfires. it was a deeply intense conference. i spoke on a panel about #metoo in academia & anthropology. preparing to speak about my experiences of sexual assault & harassment on personal, professional, institutional & societal levels was also intense. the night before i presented, i was assaulted by a man who followed me from my hotel to a restaurant pre-mtg dinner. i had to walk into the middle of traffic to safety. friends intervened. police called. i slept poorly but pulled myself together. the evening following my talk, i was aggressively propositioned literally while recounting the events of the previous night to a colleague while waiting for our order in a take out restaurant. i was shaken. i was taken in by a wonderful group of generous, funny new colleagues & friends. we played jenga & gossiped until i could barely stay awake. it was a healing night in the midst of stress, fear & exhaustion. the next morning, these photos were taken. sometimes i see deep sadness in my eyes. sometimes i see the joy of a jenga hangover. often both. i always see my grandmother in the jaunty (too jaunty, let's be real) angle of my hat. these are far from the best or my favorite photos of myself.  but there are stories carved into them. as an anthropologist and a woman, i see a value in that. next week it will be a year since i was violently assaulted in front of my home. i strive to heal myself & others a little more. thanks for being here.

text:
on average, nearly 20 people per minute are physically abused by an intimate partner in the united states. during one year, this equates to more than 10 million women and men.
1 in 4 women and 1 in 9 men experience severe intimate partner physical violence, intimate partner contact sexual violence, and/or intimate partner stalking with impacts such as injury, fearfulness, post-traumatic stress disorder, use of victim services, contraction of sexually transmitted diseases, etc.
1 in 3 women and 1 in 4 men have experienced some form of physical violence by an intimate partner. this includes a range of behaviors (e.g. slapping, shoving, pushing) and in some cases might not be considered "domestic violence." 1 in 7 women and 1 in 25 men have been injured by an intimate partner.
1 in 10 women have been raped by an intimate partner. data is unavailable on male victims.
1 in 4 women and 1 in 7 men have been victims of severe physical violence (e.g. beating, burning, strangling) by an intimate partner in their lifetime.
1 in 7 women and 1 in 18 men have been stalked by an intimate partner during their lifetime to the point in which they felt very fearful or believed that they or someone close to them would be harmed or killed.
on a typical day, there are more than 20,000 phone calls placed to domestic violence hotlines nationwide.
the presence of a gun in a domestic violence situation increases the risk of homicide by 500%.
intimate partner violence accounts for 15% of all violent crime.
women between the ages of 18-24 are most commonly abused by an intimate partner.
19% of domestic violence involves a weapon.
domestic victimization is correlated with a higher rate of depression and suicidal behavior.
only 34% of people who are injured by intimate partners receive medical care for their injuries.

text:
children and domestic violence
1 in 15 children are exposed to intimate partner violence each year, and 90% of these children are eyewitnesses to this violence.
economic impact
victims of intimate partner violence lose a total of 8.0 million days of paid work each year.
the cost of intimate partner violence exceeds $8.3 billion per year.
between 21-60% of victims of intimate partner violence lose their jobs due to reasons stemming from the abuse.
between 2003 and 2008, 142 women were murdered in their workplace by their abuser, 78% of women killed in the workplace during this timeframe.
physical/mental impact
women abused by their intimate partners are more vulnerable to contracting hiv or other sti’s due to forced intercourse or prolonged exposure to stress.
studies suggest that there is a relationship between intimate partner violence and depression and suicidal behavior.
physical, mental, and sexual and reproductive health effects have been linked with intimate partner violence including adolescent pregnancy, unintended pregnancy in general, miscarriage, stillbirth, intrauterine hemorrhage, nutritional deficiency, abdominal pain and other gastrointestinal problems, neurological disorders, chronic pain, disability, anxiety and post-traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), as well as noncommunicable diseases such as hypertension, cancer and cardiovascular diseases. victims of domestic violence are also at higher risk for developing addictions to alcohol, tobacco, or drugs.

text:
rape
1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men in the united states has been raped in their lifetime.
almost half of female (46.7%) and male (44.9%) victims of rape in the united states were raped by an acquaintance. of these, 45.4% of female rape victims and 29% of male rape victims were raped by an intimate partner.
stalking
19.3 million women and 5.1 million men in the united states have been stalked in their lifetime. 60.8% of female stalking victims and 43.5% men reported being stalked by a current or former intimate partner.
homicide
a study of intimate partner homicides found that 20% of victims were not the intimate partners themselves, but family members, friends, neighbors, persons who intervened, law enforcement responders, or bystanders.
72% of all murder-suicides involve an intimate partner; 94% of the victims of these murder suicides are female.
children and domestic violence
1 in 15 children are exposed to intimate partner violence each year, and 90% of these children are eyewitnesses to this violence.

text: השבוע בטיים אאוט: לרגל פתיחת עונת הרישום, קבלו את המדריך המלא להורה האבוד עם סקירה מקיפה של האופציות התל אביביות לחינוך אלטרנטיבי וכל מה שצריך לדעת על התפשטות החינוך הביתי בעיר, איך מגדלים בנים להיות גברים טובים בעידן #metoo – תקראו ותיישמו, אם לא בשבילם, אז בשביל האחיות שלהם. וגם, ספיינל טאפ, הגרסה התל אביבית – עשור לקדחת, להקת קאלט ללא מעריצים. זמן טוב להכין את הארון עם תחזית הטרנדים המלאה ל-2019, כולל אחד שחששתם שיחזור. 20 שנה לסופרנוס, זמן טוב לעצור ולבדוק איך היו נראים החיים שלנו בלעדיהם, כריסטיאן בייל בכוננות אוסקר וכדאי שתישרו קו, יבגני אריה, מייסד תיאטרון גשר התנגש חזיתית עם הביורקרטיה הישראלית – לפחות יצאה מזה הצגה, וגם, סצינת האוכל המתעוררת בשכונת שפירא - מיפינו לכם את מה שאסור לפספס, בתזמון מופתי עם מזג האוויר, סצינת המשלוחים בעיר משתדרגת - כל הפרטים שצריך לדעת לפני שמזמינים, מדור חדש בתרבות: נתנו ליוצרת של "מונא" המדוברת להתפרע על שני עמודים – יצא יופי! החיים קצרים, קחו טיים אאוט. להשיג חינם בבית הקפה האהוב עליכם ובסניפי אמ:פמ.

text:
the fear bucket list - from victim to power woman 
remember when i published a book? 
it has come to my attention that one of my abusers are hurting other women... which is why i’m posting this today. 
it sickens me that there is still guys out there getting away with this behaviour 😰 
if you have ever been abused or experienced some kind of sexual trauma i urge you to get a copy of my book. 
i wrote it as part of my own self healing journey and because i wanted to help other women heal and move on and live their best lives possible despite of what has happened to them. 💯 of the profits go to women and children who have survived human trafficking. help me help them and let’s stand together and create more awareness of sexual abuse still happening around the world destroying people’s lives. it has to stop! ❌
i’m channeling my anger and hurt into helping even more women this year, so please help me spread the word ❤️
.
.
.
📸 photo credit: @drkamillaholst
.
.
.

text:
нововведения в инстаграм
⠀
📍в stories снова можно включать фоновую музыку
⠀ 
недавно у пользователей instagram пропала возможность записывать истории под музыку, которая играла в других приложениях. о боги, эта возможность вернулась!
⠀
📍авторские права
⠀ 
раньше, при публикации видео, в котором была песня с авторскими правами, эту публикацию удаляли. 
сейчас instagram умеет проверять старые видео на наличие нарушений, а не только новые.
⠀
📍instagram добавил новые функции в прямые эфиры.
⠀ 
всем пользователям стали доступны две новые функции, которые сделают прямые эфиры удобнее и интереснее!
⠀
🔺вопросы и ответы; демонстрация фото
⠀

text:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i’m going to ring in 2019 with a story from last year that made my blood boil. let’s talk about lena dunham - everyone’s favorite (white) feminist.
.
in 2017, a black woman named aurora perrineau accused a male writer on lena dunham’s girls, of rape. lena dunham went on to publicly discredit the testimony of the raped woman saying “our insider knowledge of murray’s situation makes us confident that sadly this accusation is one of the 3% of assault cases that are misreported each year.”
.
basically, dunham claiming a woman lied about being raped. are you still with me? great, here’s the kicker.

late last year, lena dunham admitted that she had no inside information that supported her claim that perrineau was lying and apologized for discrediting perrineau’s testimony. in other words, dunham lied to protect a man from rape allegations. she went out of her way to discredit another woman.
.
are we outraged yet? because we should be!
.
it is important to address that dunham is white because in this sense, it highlights her privilege. we can argue about this for the next few years, but whiteness is and has always been a privilege. when a white woman speaks, her opinion will automatically be more relevant than a black womans. especially if this woman is a notorious (white) female rights activist. in the black community, it’s well known that dunham has done nothing to support women of color, but in this case she’s actively trying to discredit the testimony of a black woman in order to protect a white man.
.
it’s also clear that the empathy of dunham hasn’t evolved past her own, privileged mind. she is tone deaf on all social justice issues that aren’t directly about her and she keeps centering herself in matters where her opinions only proves how narcissistic she actually is. and yes, i am well aware that she herself has suffered sexual trauma. it doesn’t excuse her behavior because in having gone through similar experiences she should never discredit another woman’s truth.
.
when you do your best to discredit a voice of the oppressed minorities, you are standing in the way of equality.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
hello all, i feel inclined to share a story of an encounter that i faced earlier in my day to the social media world; so here it is- if you’re living local in las vegas you know that today we had nice weather, as opposed to the past few days, so i decided on my lunch that i would go for a walk. while walking down the street on my lunch in the suburbs a car full of men approached me curb side & yelled “i’m 45 & horny!” then continued to stare me down as if i was a piece of meat (i’m sure just waiting for a response, which i didn’t give them the time of day) then started laughing & sped off. •

first of all it’s january, i’m wearing a jacket & scarf- how did i even attract your attention? and second, what in your right mind would make you think that is something you can say to or treat anyone?!? if i was older/younger, had an unappealing outwardly appearance or perhaps the complete opposite gender would this have still been said to me? my guess is probably not. •

attention boys- this is not a form of flattery, i don’t feel complimented or flattered. as a woman & survivor i feel completely violated & discomfited. females are not here to serve you as your personal sex object. think of your daughters, sisters & mothers- what if this was something that was said to them & how would it make you feel? •

on the contrary, i’m blessed to have a man in my life that treats me with respect & honors me everyday as the goddess that i am. in america it has been a woman’s right to be free of discrimination & violence since 1923. that’s 96 years, and is still an ongoing issue in our society. no one should have to feel the need to be on alert for a casual walk down the street.  catcalling is harassment.  #girlpower #womensrights #metoo

text:
"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys — and the document features a warning.
“traditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit males’ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,” the report warns.

the new “guidelines for psychological practice with boys and men” defines “masculinity ideology” as “a particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewwe al of the appearance of weakness.” the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, “it’s ok to not be ok all the time.”'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews
.
.
.

the new “guidelines for psychological practice with boys and men” defines “masculinity ideology” as “a paicular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewwe al of the appearance of weakness.” the repo links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate paner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the repo include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a pa, too. he recommended they let their boys know, “it’s ok to not be ok all the time.”'
--tim fitzsimons, bcnews
.
.
.

text:
i’ve come to a season in life where i am realizing, no one around me understands quite what it is like to go through what i’ve gone through, and what i’m currently going through. i’m also realizing... no one around me really cares to try either. it’s more than time to pick up and find a way to grow. a church home where family is holding their hands in the air, thankful for what they have been given and ready for the trials that come their way because they are in relationship together. a church who isn’t just a church on sundays.
unfortunately, or fortunately, for me this means “breaking up” with many “friends” and family members and seeking a relationship through god and then my family, and eventually to building good godly relationships.
who knows, maybe i’ll finally write that book and find out i’m not completely alone.
.
.
.

text: hi, i’m nicole. i’m 26 and recently medically retired from the military. usaf vetran. i served proudly for almost 7 years as a mechanic and i miss it everyday. i am still figuring out how to cope with being a civilian. i live with a combination of different mental illnesses as indicated in my bio ^. i have been hospitalized 5 times due to suicide attempts or plans, and have attended 4 rehabs. i still struggle with self harm and substance abuse but am doing better with it! i was serving with my husband overseas before being discharged and i am now living back in my home state with my younger brother while my husband serves a remote tour overseas. i’m trying to be vulnerable and put myself more out there as a mental health advocate. i figure what better way to do that than to try and share my story. in doing so, i hope to be able to help someone else. you’re not alone and it is okay not to be okay. i do not write well, so bare with me! welcome 🌸. #medicallyretired #veteran #mentalillness #mentalhelth #bpd #ptsd #recovery #lost #selfharm #majordepressivedisorder #metoo #sexualasaultsurvivor #narcissisticabusesurvivor #survivorofabuse #suicideattemptsurvivor #fighter #mentalhealthwarrior#fightingtolivenotsurvive

text:
the morals of artists matter

i’ve been part of a recent conversation about picasso that started online, bled into real life and was partly informed by hanna gadsby’s brilliant picasso takedown in nanette.

i’ve had plenty of time to reflect on picasso’s brutal misogyny and i’ve been plenty repelled by him. for me, seeing the huge retrospective of his work at moma in 1980 was devastating. there was room after room of crying women, women whose lives he ruined with a sense of entitlement that matched his peerless ego.  he bragged about painting what you know, and what man could paint the tears of women better than he? even knowing his sordid biography didn’t give me the breadth of perspective that gadsby developed. her outrage was more articulate than mine, and the subtext, the case that morals matter in the creation and experience of art, belongs within the broader #metoo conversation. 
what surprised me in this conversation that i was part of was how many people, when asked to consider the nature of the man who made the paintings, said they’d want to hang one in their home. my sister became exasperated with me, saying i made everything political when i’d said nothing about politics. i was talking about human decency and morality and how we react to it.

the artist has a specific place in this world, and that place intersects with culture and history and their own experience in a way that is impossible to untangle. it’s the place their work comes from, and it’s different for everyone. and pablo picasso, who could have literally painted anything he dreamed up, spent his time among the tears he created, tears that fed his raging need, and celebrating the minotaur, the rapist, the monsters that feed their appetites no matter how vile or harmful they are.

that’s why i don’t want a picasso. a couple of drawings of birds and flowers and a monumental addition to the vocabulary available to all artists forever do not redeem him.

text: i don’t usually post things like this, but i will not be silent anymore. in the past few years, things have been terrible. many people have tried to take away rights of other humans, like the right to abortion, to marriage, to safety in schools and so on. this needs to stop. respect people. if someone wants an abortion, let them get one. you don’t like it? don’t get one. let everyone get married, don’t touch a person without their consent. don’t separate families.  don’t judge a person based on their race or religion. everyone deserves the right to make their own choices. as a person of the lgbtq+ community, a woman, and someone who has dealt with sexual assault, i will stand up for what’s right, so others never have to go through what i, and many others have. treat people like people, don’t discriminate against them because they are different from you, in religion, in gender, sexual identity, nationality, race, or anything else. if you don’t like this, feel free to unfollow me, as every person deserves to have rights, and not have them taken away. #feminist #feminism #marchforourlives #equality #guncontrol #metoo #metoomovement

can we now do away with the idea of “separating the art from the artist”? -
whenever a creative type (usually a man) is accused of mistreating people (usually women), a call arises to prevent those pesky details from impacting our enjoyment of the artist’s work. 
but not only these men abusers, they have used the power their creative positions to offend. 
the entertainment industry around them has been shaped and mired by that abuse of power. 
it’s time to stop enabling these men and hold them to account for the damage they have caused.

#rkelly #survivingrkelly

text:

보도에 따르면 심석희 선수는 오늘(10일) 진천선수촌으로 이동, 오후 훈련에 합류한다고 합니다.

수사 및 재판 결과를 떠나, 역사는 인간 심석희를 승자로 기록할 것입니다. 미투는 바로 그런 것입니다.

심석희 선수는 이미 더 나은 세상을 만들었습니다!

정치하는엄마들은 심석희 선수를 비롯한 전세계 모든 미투 운동가에게 다시 한 번 존경과 감사의 마음을 보냅니다.

엄정한 수사와 재판과 처벌이 이뤄질 수 있도록 sns 프로필 사진과 커버 사진을 바꾸는 온라인 행동에 동참해주세요!

phenomenal women: we know them, we raise them, we believe them, we are them. 
kicking off 2019 with my proudest achievement yet: a benefit concert on the eve of the 46th anniversary of roe v. wade to raise funds for planned parenthood. the concert, titled phenomenal women, draws inspiration from the poem by maya angelou and song by @lauramvula of almost the same name, “phenomenal woman.” this concert will feature three powerfully female acts: @bandamagda, @briaskonberg and @likwuid. you’ll find me hosting the night, jumping in with banda magda, and generally celebrating the magic this evening will inevitably conjure. ✨ come rock out in the name of women’s rights and support, january 21st at @nationalsawdust! link in bio.

text: i believe it is time that i post this image once more, to drive home a point. i was going to believe i had gone through with my decrying of r. kelly publicly, and i certainly gave my piece... but it had recently become clear to me that there was a situation in my life where someone i knew, trusted and even worked together with for nearly three years was a sexual predator who tried to prey on a young black girl who for protection purposes will be left unnamed... he had begun calling her his girlfriend, when she was not of any legal age in america to be able to give consent. i will ask that none of you request information on this situation on this situation, as it is already being dealt with by the proper people in his life. however, as a survivor of sexual assault myself who was molested by a worship leader in college, in a state far from my own away from my parents, i am expressing with great and unbelievable pain the implications of potentially having saved someone’s life. it is a welcome thing that i had to do what was right, but the psychic toll of seeing yourself reflected in a situation where even your defenses were lowered makes you relive your own assault not on the level of traumatic anxiety, but of traumatic understanding and empathy. you know how when guts in berserk was struggling with ptsd from his own assault? while i don’t have ptsd, it’s like seeing that you rescued yourself when you couldn’t have been rescued in the first place. that is why now more than ever i bring attention to mute r. kelly and the work they are doing to save these girls. please: don’t let another girl end up like aaliyah. that i ever had to deal with the experience of fighting a child predator who i once called my best friend is something i cannot believe. #muterkelly #aaliyah #metoo

text:
to include this leaf in the survivor tree project is nothing short of an honor and is truly a testament to the bonds of survivorship. anne lauren of @blue_and_lavender was introduced to me by the inimitable founder of @seenheardbelieved (more on her later), and from the moment i heard her voice, i knew this woman is a force. i’ve never met her in person- we spoke over the airwaves of approximately 2500 miles; but it felt as if she was sitting right next to me- opening herself up, leaning emphatically into every animated word, reassuring me that through our advocacy we will change the world. she is authentic and unabashed and it is such a privilege that i now know her even remotely. •
anne’s survivor story details how she had to rebuild her life after uncovering repressed sexual abuse memories at 24. these memories stretch back to the tender age of 3, involving three male members of her family. soon after, anne confronted her family and made the heartbreaking decision to walk away when they didn’t believe her. she then faced the challenges stacked against survivors by the justice and healthcare systems while at the same time supporting herself through an expensive recovery process. while today she is focused on her own healing, she has made it a priority to build a network of support for fellow trauma survivors. “i share my story to encourage survivors and inspire them to seek healing, advocacy, safety, and justice. i think life is so beautiful and that this type of violence cannot be tolerated!” this incredible woman wears armor forged in pain and heartache, yet speaks and lives with such compassion and fire- i’m in awe. and i’m so grateful for her. check out her ig page and website link in her bio- the online survivor support community that she and her team have created is truly a gift. she is, in a word, an inspiration. from the bottom of my heart, anne- thank you… ✨🌱 click the link in my bio if others would like to contribute your story to the survivor tree project. #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #rapesurvivor #sexualassaultsurvivor #csasurvivor #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #thesurvivortreeproject
name: Mel Hanley | Survivor Advocate

text:
you go from dancing and laughing with your bestfriend and seeing her beautiful smile to getting a picture of her beaten and bloody. happy new year right? you are the bravest women i know! i almost lost you sis! you sit back and say damn ...what could have i done to prevent this. shit, i’m the one that caused y’all to meet! our stories are never ours but used for gods grace ...your bravery has allowed me to stand up with you and say me too. you are not alone ...and i will walk through this journey of healing . god put this burden on you to share your story and you were obedient to his cries! 20 stitches, surgery and the emotional torment will never take away how beautiful you are inside and out ! god truly took his time with you . this is so tough to watch but he doesn’t choose the weak to go through his chosen trials and testimonies! i love you my beautiful black queen! i am here with you every step of the way @daiopusdotcom ♥️ #queen #brave #igotyou #thisisnotlove #free #life #metoo #noshame #godsstory #blessings
.
.
.
.
"do you know new years day doesn’t even start until march yet we celebrate january 1st? never again will i celebrate something that i don’t believe in! that includes being loved for all the wrong reasons. i’ve been sitting in one place for the past 67 minutes writing then deleting, changing my words, then repeating them with new diction just to end up saying the same thing again... “patience is a terrible thing to waste” and our time was up that night. that was the worst fight we’ve ever had, and i’m glad. one minute i’m mad then i think of missing you and i’m sad, just to pray god continue works on us because the truth is unmasked. i forgive you. i forgive me. if you know me well enough this mixtape must be released poetically. - @daiopusdotcom "

text:
#metoo argentino: actrices vs juan darthés. parte 1

el #metoo se vitaliza en américa latina, cada día aparecen casos nuevos. uno de los más recientes ocurrió en argentina. los hechos: juan darthés, actor de televisión que desarrolló su carrera en argentina fue denunciado por la actriz thelma fardín. en una rueda de prensa (donde estuvo acompañada del colectivo actrices argentinas) y por medio de un video realizado especialmente para la ocasión, fardín lo acusó de haberla violado cuando todavía era menor de edad y trabajaban juntos en una serie de televisión. días después darthés lo negó en una entrevista.

para conocer los pormenores sobre este caso solo basta poner el nombre de alguno de los involucrados en google. los medios de comunicación argentinos (y del mundo) han publicado un gran número de notas sobre el asunto. esta no es la primera acusación para darthés, años antes otra actriz lo había denunciado por “excesos” en el set de grabación. luego de la acusación de fardín, otras mujeres se han sumado a la lista declarando que el actor mantiene conductas impropias.

hay una acusación abierta en nicaragua en su contra (lugar donde supuestamente se dio la violación) pero no existe el dictamen de un juez, no hay sentencia. en teoría juan darthés es inocente (como cualquiera de nosotros) hasta que se demuestre lo contrario.

escribo en teoría porque en la práctica no es así.

darthés ha sido condenado socialmente. la presión mediática fue tan abrasiva en argentina, donde residía, que tuvo que irse a pasar las fiestas navideñas a brasil, su país de origen. en los medios se ha dichohasta la saciedad que es culpable del delito de violación, sin que haya concluido una investigación que lo demuestre.

particularmente me parece grave acusar a alguien (hombre o mujer) y etiquetarlo de culpable sin un juicio de por medio. 
continua en el siguiente post. 
completa en #elnacional ➡ http://www.el-nacional.com/autores/luisa-ugueto .

text: and then there are days when i just miss him. even though i know he never loved me. even though i know we’re better off apart. even though i love my husband completely and i’m happy in our relationship. even though i know he’s toxic, troubled, and damaged beyond the ability to ever have a meaningful, healthy relationship romantically or otherwise. i don’t want him back in my life. for whatever reason the wound left by his abrupt departure from my life aches, like an old battle scar or broken bone before the weather changes. it’s not even a specific day, or any specific trigger. it’s completely random. most of the memories have faded, but every once and a while there he is. stuck in my minds eye until he slowly fades away again. 🤷🏻‍♀️ #ptsdproblems #recovery #abusesurvivor #metoo

text:
#metoo argentino: actrices vs juan darthés. parte 2. parte 1 en el post anterior. 
si bien es cierto que todos (hombres y mujeres, no es un tema de género) tenemos derecho a denunciar cuando se ha cometido un abuso en nuestra contra. también es verdad que el mero hecho de denunciarlo no es un aval. no debería serlo. mucha gente miente: hombres y mujeres.

existe la presunción de inocencia y el beneficio de la duda. aunque cada uno es libre de creer la versión que quiera.

el problema no está en creerle a  thelma fardín o a juan darthés. si comentas tu opinión en un sofá con tus amigos o encerrado en cuatro paredes no hay inconveniente. pero hacer declaraciones públicas y participar en  escraches ya entra en otro terreno, en uno turbio y peligroso.

afirmar que una persona es culpable de algo tan grave, sin que exista una investigación que  lo avale, es por lo menos el inicio de lo que llamarían siglos atrás una caza de brujas.

no hay que perder de vista que la condena social, la justicia por mano propia es también un delito.

sucedió recientemente con morgan freeman, el actor de hollywood. fue acusado de actos impropios por más de 10 personas. todas las denuncias quedaron deslegitimadas. ¿qué pasa en esos casos con la reputación del supuesto abusador? ¿qué debería hacer freeman? ¿quién le devuelve su buen nombre?

las víctimas de abuso sexual merecen compasión y respeto. validar sus denuncias equivale a comenzar una investigación que esclarezca los hechos.

sin embargo, es elemental tener en cuenta que la defensa de los derechos de cualquier persona deberíanestar siempre basadosen principios de justicia y equidad. sin importar el género de la víctima y del acusado.

se supone que todos queremos verdadera  justicia y sobre todo un trato igualitario para hombres y mujeres ¿o no es así?

las víctimas de abuso sexual merecen compasión y respeto. validar sus denuncias equivale a comenzar una investigación que esclarezca los hechos.

sin embargo, es elemental tener en cuenta que la defensa de los derechos de cualquier persona deberíanestar siempre basadosen principios de justicia y equidad. sin importar el género de la víctima y del acusado.

se supone que todos queremos verdadera  justicia y sobre todo un trato igualitario para hombres y mujeres ¿o no es así?

text:
i know that it is easier to say this quote than to actually get it done, right?! but i am sharing this with you just to remind you that there is no point of focusing on your past because it won't change what happened to you. it is a sad reality that i ended up realizing. it is a waste of time to constantly go back to your past, hoping that somehow all your bad memories will be erased. it doesn't work like this and sadly, it won't. that is the reason why we all need to focus on our future, focus on things we can actually control like our reaction through life challenges. we are the results of all the decisions and reactions we've made through life. my healing journey isn't easy at all, in my case, it is actually harder than going through the trauma itself. but still, to heal is the best decision i have ever made.

the voice of peace ❤

text:
💎caso:
ena xitlalhi [parte 1]
junio 2017, méxico

ena xitlalhi alperte chávez, estudiante de 19 años de edad, era de nayarit y tenía un hijo de poco más de un año con el qu3 vivía en el municipio de xalisco.
xitlalhi fue encontrada por sus familiates en su domicilio, ella estaba boca arriba, a un costado de su cama, una de las paredes estaba manchada de sangre y ena estaba sin vida. junto a ella, se encontraba su hijo, quien lloraba junto al cuerpo de su madre que había sido degollada, y que además, presentaba dos heridas en el cuello.
el asesino de xitlalhi pudo ser ubicado gracias a un mensaje de voz que ella había enviado por whatsapp a un amigo, a quien pidió ayuda.
"mi vecino se brincó ma barda, ¡ayúdame, ayúdame!", decía el breve audio que el joven escuchó al día siguiente del homicidio.
tras oir la grabación, el joven cuya identidad no fue revelada, entregó el mensaje como prueba a la policía investigadora, esto permitió a las autoridades emitir la orden de aprehensión para capturar a ignacio "n" también conocido como "el nacho", de aproximadamente 35 años, a quien se señala como responsable de acabar con la vida de la joven madre.
el sospechoso había intentado huir, pero si domicilio era vigilado por policías. ignacio "n" habitaba una casa junto al domicilio de la víctima, donde fueron encontrados el arma del crimen, además de otras pruebas de su culpabilidad en el homicidio.
los hechos en los que participó el acusado y costó la vida de la víctima sucedieron a las 00:30 hrs del día domingo 2 de julio, ena xitlalhi estaba en su hogar con su pequeño de 1 año de edad, cuando se dio cuenta que su vecino había brindado la barda y se encontraba en el patio de su casa forzando la puerta para entrar.
el ministerio público señaló que ignacio, al entrar a la vivienda, empujó a la joven madre con fuerza hasta llevarla a la recámara y con cuchillo en mano le provocó la muerte.
el hombre salió del lugar con la cartera y el celular de la víctima, las cuales fueron encontrados en el cateo a su domicilio. [+]
·
·
·

ena xitlalhi [parte 2]
julio 2017, méxico
[+]
el acusado dijo en tres ocasiones: "soy culpable, señor"; pero esta declaración no fue tomada como formal.
el vecino de xitlalhi fue acusado del delito de homicidio calificado, con las agravantes de ensañamiento, crueldad, alevosía y ventaja.
el juez ordenó el internamiento del culpado en el centro de reinserción social venustiano carranza de tepic.
yurhildy elizabeth alperte, hermana de la víctima ha posteado mensaje de dolor en sus redes sociales para lidiar con la pérdida.
josé luis pérez hernández, exesposo de ena también aprovechó su perfil de facebook para enviar un agradecimiento y una despedida póstuma a la madre su hijo de un año. ¿tú qué opinas sobre este feminicidio? déjanos tu opinión 👇 no se queden calladas.

text:
9|365: i read something the other day that stuck with me all day, & had my mind in a frenzy. .
“you’ll never be too much for someone who can’t get enough of you.”
🤯
.
my mind was literally blown by reading it.. i read it over and over actually. .
& then yesterday  my sissy texted me saying she was on chapter 4 of #girlwashyourface & she loved @msrachelhollis & is now going to be just as obsessed as i was. 
tbh, i started to cry. she thanked me for introducing her, asked about the #starttodaymorningshow & was soo excited. cue my heart exploding of girl power happiness.

but i knew that the next chapter she would read would probably hit her as hard as it did me.. .
chapter 5 of girl, wash your face is pretty much exactly about the line i quoted earlier. about how as women we let loving someone be enough for us. later last night she sent a screen shot of part of the chapter, and underneath all it said was as follows:
i’m crying
i feel this in my soul. .
chapter 5 was the first chapter that i broke down during when i first read this book. it hit me, & it hit me hard.
and as i reminisced i kept thinking about us as women.. .
.
at some point us women started making our self smaller, in every aspect of life. striving to never being too much. we are told by society we can’t do certain things, we aren’t as valuable as a man so they pay them more, we should work as if we don’t take care of tiny humans yet mom so hard as if we don’t leave them for eight + hours a day to work. we aren’t pushed to go after our dreams, until recently. & maybe it’s just that i’m noticing it more..
maybe it’s in the era of #metoo 
i can’t quite put my finger on it, but what i can tell you - women are sick to death of being stifled, 
of having people dull our sparkle. 
if i know anything it’s that a tribe is comin’ & let me tell you darlin - 
2019, is female. 💋
.
so on this #wcw i’m gonna shout out to my sissy i miss you like crazy, i am soo glad you are reading this book & the birthday girl herself @msrachelhollis for writing the book that changed it all.
.
.
.
#madefor100more #nydy19
name: kacicollins

i believe in energy ❤️ i believe that we are not part of the universe, we are universe.

as these movement (#metoo #blacklivesmatter #blackgirlsmatter #womenempowerment #survingrkelly #muterkelly #feminist ...) are taking place... let’s remember that everything is perfect.

we need to speak of these movements so we can overcome them.

the best state of mind is to say thank you in good times and thank you in these “experiences”. there is no such thing as bad times.

one love,
ruth

text: #longpostalert ⁉️📵 so i’m not an r.kelly victim but definitely a #chicago girl that got pregnant 🤰🏽 at 14 by a 23 yr.old man. i now have a beautiful 18 going on 19 adult child. so #metoo ☝️😢 i’m numb to the reality of how horrible this is because it’s was/is my life. no one ever stood-up for me 😭😢😭😢 i still have all these issues associated with the bags left for me to carry. i never look like what i’ve been through. i have gotten professional help before to deal with some things but i’m still dealing. i’m so blessed that i turned out better than everyone thought. i didn’t even complete 9th grade. i got my ged pregnant at 16 by my 24 boyfriend now ex husband 🤷🏽‍♀️💆🏽‍♀️🤦🏽‍♀️ so 2 men very much older than me. i’m happy people are becoming conscious of this behavior. i can’t help but feel disconnected from the astonishment of others though🤨🤔 this is not new people!!! not right of course but not new at all. we’d have to come for alot of men if everyone wants to be honest. however i think this is important to prevent more harmful statutory situations. i deserved this type justice too and so do many other women. 🙏🏾😢 i’m sad to say i witnessed this type of thing all the time growing up in chicago. i’m sure it’s all over the country tho. i will say my #babydaddy did have r kelly playing all the time in the background #twelveplay2 to be exact #smh and we definitely went #halfonababy 🤰🏽🤦🏽‍♀️🤷🏽‍♀️ 😬i’m not watching this crap 💩 #btw #mytruth #portiaisshe #letsgo #livelifenow

text:
no matter how slow and covert this abuse was, let’s be honest: if most of us had a bit more self respect and knowingly deserving of better treatment, we would’ve either a) set boundaries/drawn the line so much sooner and/or b) we would’ve left. @emilyskyefit bravely posted a great video today sharing her story of her abusive ex and the terrifying things he did to her and his own family. she shared why she didn’t leave sooner which included the fact that he threatened to harm her family and her dog. what stuck out most was how she went into detail about how she felt she didn’t deserve love and believed she wouldn’t do better. how crazy is that? victims self blame and shame ourselves enough. if we work on ourselves and love ourselves, we would never ignore so many red flags. we would recognize the mistreatment so much sooner and get out. this is so important to work on!! you do deserve love. you do deserve happiness. abuse is not your fault!

text:
i go not quietly
.
i go not quietly
i go as perfume unidentified
a shelter of pulsating pink
for those willing 
to disrobe their darkness
and make it a doormat
before stepping in
my no is not an invitation
and my wall 
is simply to manage the wolves
for my heart fills the pen
in which i stand
.
i go not quietly
i go as perfume unidentified
my delicate arms have constructed 
all of my furniture
my gentleness is gorilla glue
the tapestries off my tongue
are worth listening to
and my preciousness is pie 
only in a worthy man’s sky
.
i go not quietly
i go loudly 
with a quiet truth
for i am lady
and i sing of everyone’s perfume
.
some of it you’ll like
and some of it you'll not
.
.

.

text:
with all of the allegations circling r kelly i get this overwhelming sickening feeling when i see so many people still blaming the victims. are we that lost that we can't find any compassion for our own people. let us not be mistaken that he is one of many predators. i am forced to think about my own experiences and those of my friends and family. my art has always been an escape from reality and yet again it sheds light on some of the darkest subjects i've ever had to face
.
no woman should ever be silenced🖤
.

text:
this is sick. and horrifying. she cannot be the only one, there are more. (more info below)
•
01/09/19 at phoenix (cnn) police investigators have begun to gather dna from men who work at an arizona care facility where a woman in a vegetative state gave birth last month.

phoenix police sgt. tommy thompson said wednesday the woman and child, who was in medical distress after being delivered december 29, remain in the hospital.

cnn is not reporting the woman's name because she is the victim of sexual abuse.

cnn affiliate kpho/ktvk has reported the woman has been in a vegetative state for 14 years, quoting a source familiar with the situation. the woman has been a patient at this facility for at least a decade following a near-drowning incident when she was 15 years old, the phoenix-based station quoted its source as saying

hacienda "will accept nothing less than a full accounting of this absolutely horrifying situation, an unprecedented case that has devastated everyone involved, from the victim and her family to hacienda staff at every level of our organization," said gary orman, executive vice president of hacienda healthcare's board of directors.

last week the state's department of economic security sent investigators to the facility for health and safety checks. spokesman brett bezio said the work was finished but didn't give any details about the results of the visits with patients.

text:
this week in #womenswire we address the #survivingrkelly documentary, which at its root points to people not believing or significantly valuing black girls and women. we can and must change the culture, we can and must make sure that #metoo⁠⁠ is a movement that values and protects all women and femmes. in parallel we talk about #cyntoiabrown’s sentence getting commuted this week—and commit to educating ourselves and organizing to free other survivors of abuse who are imprisoned. the takeaway from both of these news stories? trust, believe, protect black women and girls and, if you identify as a white ally speak up and amplify this critical conversation. 
what else? we’ve got jobs, tons of events, and last but not least a wholehearted endorsement of @ocasio2018’s dancing (and any other woman/femme and member of congress) ✨✨link in bio! #trustblackwomen #believeblackgirls #survivedandpunished

text:
#metoo 
these days all my thoughts are in my hometown of vladivostok where one brave woman katya fedorova started her fight against the wall of silence, accusing her rapist in public on her facebook page. it turned out that the rapist is a super powerful man, a co-founder a vladivostok media holding "prima-media". i do not know katya personally. i've been living away from vladivostok for quite a long time, but i still feel a strong connection with the city. i've been following the wave of bullying that has fallen on katya's shoulders these days. i do not know how she is dealing with it. vladivostok is not a very large russian city. the intellectual community is rather small and everyone knows each other - so, you can imagine what katya is risking in such a strong patriarchic society as russia’s. katya is a journalist, an activist, a founder of a feminist project "feminologi" that has given voice to women experiencing different forms of discrimination. she has helped many women and now she is herself in trouble. this is a radical notion for a local community to understand that everything a man does after a woman says "no" is violence. if you have seen the tv series "big little lies" you ought to remember jane’s story, one of the main characters who experienced rape and lived in constant fear, with post-traumatic stress disorder, keeping a gun under her pillow for 7 years. what was rape in this tv show? she agreed to go to a hotel with a guy she met in a bar, she agreed on sex with him, but she did not agree to accept violence against her! how can we talk about consensual sex when a woman is traumatized, suffers bruises all over her body and is left with a broken face and in tears? why is it even an issue whether katya went with the perpetrator to a restaurant or not, whether she drank wine or not, whether she let him to walk her home or not? she was traumatized physically and mentally. that is called violence! and the bullying in social and mass media that she experiences is called victim blaming, removing once again the focus from a rapist to his victim. maybe we can start erasing some harmful patriarchal presentiments (more in comments)...

how many hours, days, weeks, months, or years have you spent in misery over your abuse history? that emotional build up creates pressure and that’s what creates a diamond. let go of the pressure by releasing the stuck emotions from your body through an emotional release process that resonates with you. my emotional release transformation process is designed to help you release so you can excavate the diamond that you are. .
.
.
at the core of every abuse story is is the possibility for transformation. you’re a diamond in there. they can’t break you. start digging. consultations are free. link in my bio to schedule. .
.
.

text:
“when a call for peaceful protests in support of korean independence came in spring 1919, a 16-year-old girl named yu gwan-sun became the face of a nation’s collective yearning for freedom.

yu was a student at ewha haktang in seoul, which was established by american missionaries as the first modern educational institution for women in korea. on march 1, 1919, yu and four classmates joined others taking to the streets with cries of “mansei!” (“long live korean independence!”) in one of the earliest protests against japanese colonial rule. amid the demonstration, the declaration of independence — written by the publisher choe nam-seon  and signed by 33 korean cultural and religious leaders — was recited at seoul’s pagoda park.” https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/28/obituaries/overlooked-yu-gwan-sun.html “3·1운동 100주년을 맞는다. 한국전쟁과 함께 현대 한국 최대의 고비요 사건이다. 오늘의 우리를 만든 정신의 원류요 사상의 뿌리다. 미래의 가치요 지향이다. 우리 자신이 세계 모든 사람과 똑같이 ‘스스로’ 자유요 독립임과, ‘함께’ 평화요 존엄임을 세계만방에 알린 날이다.” “3·1은 무엇을 남겼나? 무엇보다 3·1은 민주와 공화가 만난 첫 민주공화국인 대한민국 임시정부를 낳았다. 민주공화의 첫 토대였다. 그러나 임시정부는 바로 파벌과 갈등에 시달렸고 통합은 무너졌다. 게다가 공산주의계열은 3·1 이후의 ‘대한’ ‘민주공화’를 부정, ‘조선’공산당·‘조선’혁명·‘조선’민족해방으로 갈려나갔다. (훗날 ‘조선’인민공화국·‘조선’민주주의인민공화국도 같았다) ‘대한’을 부인하려 ‘조선’총독부·‘조선’지배·식민지 ‘조선’을 말한 일제처럼. 
광복 이후 첫 3·1운동 기념식은 좌우로 완전히 갈렸고, 한쪽의 기념식은 임정계열 인사들이 투척한 수류탄으로 아수라장이 되었다. 통합과 공존의 3·1정신은 사라졌다. 전후 세계 분할점령-연합점령 국가 중 단 한 나라도 이토록 빨리 적대하지 않았다는 점에서 3·1정신은 일제 직후 우리 스스로 두 번째로 죽인 것이었다. 
근대 이래 지금 우리는 우리를 식민지로 만들었던 상대 나라와 국력에서 가장 근접해있다. 누천년 조공관계를 유지하였던 제국과는 전후 내내 민주제도와 경제발전, 기술과 삶의 수준에서 앞서 왔다. 전자는 500년래, 후자는 2000년래 처음이다. 이제 민족주의를 넘어 세계주의를 품을 때다. 
3·1 100년. ‘항일’과 ‘독립운동’의 좁은 의식세계로부터 벗어나 우리의 정신세계와 미래공간을 활짝 열자. 우리의 뿌리는 항일보다 깊고 줄기는 독립보다 크다. 대저 수오지심과 자기혁신에 바탕해 대통합·민주공화·세계시민·보편평화로 나아간 3·1정신의 대해로 사뭇 달려가자. 그리하여 최고 최량의 민주공화국으로 발전하여 세계 보편가치와 이상을 끌고 가보자. 우리 한번 해보자.” [중앙일보] [중앙시평] 3·1운동 100주년에 부쳐 
https://mnews.joins.com/article/23254374 “세계적으로 ‘미투(#metoo) 운동’이 확산되면서 여성 권리와 여성 리더에 대한 이야기를 많이 한다. 한국엔 100년 전 억압된 사회에서 떨쳐 일어난 강인한 여성이 있었다는 걸 알리고 싶다.” http://news.donga.com/pdf/3/all/20190110/93628388/1

광복 이후 첫 3·1운동 기념식은 좌우로 완전히 갈렸고, 한쪽의 기념식은 임정계열 인사들이 투척한 수류탄으로 아수라장이 되었다. 통합과 공존의 3·1정신은 사라졌다. 전후 세계 분할점령-연합점령 국가 중 단 한 나라도 이토록 빨리 적대하지 않았다는 점에서 3·1정신은 일제 직후 우리 스스로 두 번째로 죽인 것이었다. 
근대 이래 지금 우리는 우리를 식민지로 만들었던 상대 나라와 국력에서 가장 근접해있다. 누천년 조공관계를 유지하였던 제국과는 전후 내내 민주제도와 경제발전, 기술과 삶의 수준에서 앞서 왔다. 전자는 500년래, 후자는 2000년래 처음이다. 이제 민족주의를 넘어 세계주의를 품을 때다. 
3·1 100년. ‘항일’과 ‘독립운동’의 좁은 의식세계로부터 벗어나 우리의 정신세계와 미래공간을 활짝 열자. 우리의 뿌리는 항일보다 깊고 줄기는 독립보다 크다. 대저 수오지심과 자기혁신에 바탕해 대통합·민주공화·세계시민·보편평화로 나아간 3·1정신의 대해로 사뭇 달려가자. 그리하여 최고 최량의 민주공화국으로 발전하여 세계 보편가치와 이상을 끌고 가보자. 우리 한번 해보자.” [중앙일보] [중앙시평] 3·1운동 100주년에 부쳐 
 “세계적으로 ‘미투( 운동’이 확산되면서 여성 권리와 여성 리더에 대한 이야기를 많이 한다. 한국엔 100년 전 억압된 사회에서 떨쳐 일어난 강인한 여성이 있었다는 걸 알리고 싶다.”

text:
can i be honest with you?

i struggle sometimes. the world of emotions and feelings have been foreign and undesirable for me. i've had a lifetime of bottling up my thoughts and opinions, experiences and emotions, and i did it out of survival. 
to survive childhood sexual abuse, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive childhood domestic abuse, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive from neglect, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive being unseen and unheard, i had to disconnect from myself. to survive my heartbreak when my mum died, i had to disconnect from myself.

do you see a theme here? by the time i got to adulthood, i didn't know how i felt. correction; i didn't feel. numbness followed by numbness.

but all the sadness, distraught, anger, upset, all the pain and disappointment i felt over the years, it didn't just disappear. it was shoved to the back or my mind and forgotten about, but it didn't forget me.

i've mentioned before about how my anxiety affects me and how depression creeps up on me every year. last year i opted to self refer to nhs counselling. i opted to take anti depressants to manage the extreme emotion i was beginning to feel.

it's like being upset but having to spend time working out why. and often it's not even current, it's feelings from the past triggered by something in the present.

i've been working on reconnecting to myself and it has been hard, it has been emotional and it has been draining. in my counselling sessions, i talk about things i've never dared to say out loud, and leave feeling a raw emotional pain in my chest, the after effect of holding back my recovery of a traumatic past; 
sexual abuse, rape, domestic violence, bereavement, emotional abuse, rape, manipulation, gaslighting, financial abuse, harassment, post natal depression, anxiety, depression.

my boundaries and self-preservation is at an all time high, but i'm sharing this because i know some of you want to reconnect with yourselves.

i want to say, yes it is hard. but you are strong. and you can do this.

we can do this.

#letshealtogether ❤
